to explain a problem.

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:40.820
It was a problem in a workforce.

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:43.370
It was a problem
with black women

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:46.490
who were basically saying that
in the industry that they were

00:04:46.490 --> 00:04:48.080
in, it was the
auto manufacturing

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:51.020
industry, that they were
being discriminated against.

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:53.930
They couldn't get hired.

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:56.090
The problem was
that the courts had

00:04:56.090 --> 00:04:58.490
a version of what race
discrimination looked like

00:04:58.490 --> 00:05:00.680
and it was what
happened to black men.

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:02.270
And they had a
version of what gender

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:04.130
discrimination looked
like, and it was

00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:06.140
what happened to white women.

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:07.700
These black women
were saying, well,

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:09.440
what happens to
white women and what

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:12.200
happens to black men
doesn't really tell you much

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:14.360
about what's happening to us.

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:17.240
So white women, yes,
they are experiencing

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:19.220
a form of discrimination here.

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:23.120
They can't work in any other
place in this industry but as

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:28.190
a secretary or a receptionist
or a telephone operator.

00:05:28.190 --> 00:05:30.440
The way they experience
gender discrimination

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:33.020
isn't exactly the same way
that we're experiencing

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:34.430
gender discrimination.

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.890
They have to work
as secretaries.

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:39.200
We can't work at all.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:41.720
Or they'll say
African-American men are

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:43.760
experiencing discrimination.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:47.150
When they apply here at this
auto manufacturing plant,

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:51.500
they're only allowed to work
in the front, on the floor,

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.870
in the heavy jobs, in
the dangerous jobs.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:55.430
That's discrimination.

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:57.620
But their discrimination
is not the same as ours,

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.410
because as women, we
can't even get that work.

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:02.300
So the point of
intersectionality

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:05.000
was to say, we can
figure this out

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.500
if we just use a real common
metaphor, an intersection.

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.650
So some part of the way that
workforce was structured,

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:15.170
the roads, was a
racial structure.

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:16.400
Black jobs are here.

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:18.240
White jobs are here.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:21.350
The other part of the structure
was a gender structure.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:22.850
Women can work here.

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:24.890
Women cannot work here.

00:06:24.890 --> 00:06:27.670
If you are a black
person who is a woman,

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:30.020
you are actually
situated where those two

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:31.820
policies come together.

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:35.210
So the traffic, the policy,
the hiring decisions

00:06:35.210 --> 00:06:39.410
that go down the race road
or the gender road actually

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:42.470
creates an intersection
where those people who

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:45.440
are black and female are
subject to discrimination.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:49.260
So it's not really
a complicated idea,

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:51.410
but it is one that
requires people

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:53.540
to understand that
intersectionality is not

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:55.740
just about identity.

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.820
It's about identity in a context
in which your identity makes

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:02.030
a difference in your
access to equality

00:07:02.030 --> 00:07:04.289
or your availability
to discrimination.

