They know I'm not white,
but they know I'm not black.

00:11:12.536 --> 00:11:14.160
Actually I had a
student in South Korea

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:16.649
once say to me, when I
was teaching ESL there,

00:11:16.649 --> 00:11:18.690
said teacher, you're not
white, you're not black.

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:19.740
What are you?

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:24.149
And I was like, that's another
two hours that we get to kill.

00:11:24.149 --> 00:11:25.440
But it was a poignant question.

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:27.640
I mean we're in this
tiny town in South Korea.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:30.660
This was in 2002.

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:32.400
And so they didn't
have a lot of exposure

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.410
to anything other
than mainstream media.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:37.620
And mainstream media, as someone
that works in the mainstream

00:11:37.620 --> 00:11:39.300
media now, that
wasn't always the path

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:40.800
that I thought I
was going to be on.

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:43.800
And the images that we get
of who we are from mainstream

00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:46.500
media, for me growing
up as a Latina,

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.290
as a Puerto Rican woman,
but also as a working

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:50.940
class and poor family.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:54.360
I lived in public housing
for the first 20, 21

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:55.090
years of my life.

00:11:55.090 --> 00:11:58.222
So right there, if I say,
I grew up in the projects.

00:11:58.222 --> 00:12:00.180
Think about what's in
your mind right now, what

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:01.266
you're imagining.

00:12:01.266 --> 00:12:02.640
If I hadn't said
that, and I just

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:05.940
sat here and said "New
York Times," CNN, traveled

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:09.510
the world, taught in South
Korea, like your image of me

00:12:09.510 --> 00:12:11.940
is very different probably
than what you have in your mind

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:15.180
right now if I say I spent 21
years in the projects, right?

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:18.440
Now it's like, oh, OK,
that's a change, right?

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:20.400
But that's a core identity.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:22.480
That's a core part of who I am.

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:25.500
But also in the conversations
around intersectionality,

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.620
we often forget about class.

00:12:27.620 --> 00:12:30.540
I think class is one of the
most underrepresented parts

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:33.120
of the conversation, and
an area that so many of us

00:12:33.120 --> 00:12:37.150
can connect on and we
tend to not do that.

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:39.340
And I say, and of
course, I'm a woman.

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:42.000
I'm a heterosexual woman so
that presents its own set

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.330
of challenges in many cases.

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:48.400
And I'm a woman of a certain
age, I won't say where,

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:52.650
but probably a little
older than a couple of you.

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:55.485
And so all of these
things are connected,

00:12:55.485 --> 00:12:56.670
and none of these things.

00:12:56.670 --> 00:12:59.040
But yet growing up,
there was never really

00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:01.320
a space for people like me.

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:03.482
And when Kim and I were
talking before we got here,

00:13:03.482 --> 00:13:05.190
I said one of my goals
is to really start

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:07.349
to create more spaces--

00:13:07.349 --> 00:13:08.640
oops, sorry, there's my water--

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:11.880
where people who were
living these sorts

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.550
of intersectional lives can
come together, where you see

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:16.590
yourself reflected.

00:13:16.590 --> 00:13:18.160
So I said I grew
up in the projects.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:21.222
Everybody probably has an image
of what that looks like, right?

00:13:21.222 --> 00:13:21.930
Well, guess what?

00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:23.638
There are also people
in the projects who

00:13:23.638 --> 00:13:26.190
work every day
and raise families

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:29.610
and aren't drug addicted
or any other thing.

00:13:29.610 --> 00:13:32.280
But there are lots
of pathologies that

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:33.810
also happen in public housing.

00:13:33.810 --> 00:13:36.390
So being able to survive
that was one thing,

00:13:36.390 --> 00:13:39.720
but being able to also not get
involved in that lifestyle,

00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:42.190
you didn't really
feel like I fit there.

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:45.690
But I didn't necessarily
fit in certain other areas.

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:49.860
And when it came to being a
feminist, which I define myself

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:51.870
as, that was also something
that was like, whoa,

00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:55.140
this is a really
white conversation

00:13:55.140 --> 00:13:58.740
that really tends to be
led by white wealthy,

00:13:58.740 --> 00:14:01.539
or women of means, educated
white women of means.

00:14:01.539 --> 00:14:03.330
So while I believed in
a lot of the tenets,

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:06.220
I felt like that conversation
was very limited.

00:14:06.220 --> 00:14:09.960
And it did not
embrace the totality

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.880
of who I am as a
person, of what I

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:14.490
have to deal with as a woman
of color, of what I have

00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:16.800
to deal with as a woman who
came from a working class

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:17.820
background.

00:14:17.820 --> 00:14:19.280
And so there are so many of--

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:22.140
and believe me, I traveled the
world for four years on my own.

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:24.640
There weren't a lot of people
that looked like me out there.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:25.890
This whole backpacking thing?

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:29.057
That was a very white thing
to do back in the day.

00:14:29.057 --> 00:14:30.390
Everybody was like what do you--

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:30.890
what?

00:14:30.890 --> 00:14:32.440
You don't even know
anybody in China?

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:33.840
No, but I'm out.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:36.650
And then even being in
China was like what?

00:14:36.650 --> 00:14:38.100
Like you're not blond?

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:39.740
People who just didn't get it.

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:41.520
And I mean, it was an
amazing experience.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:43.330
But it also shows
the limitations

00:14:43.330 --> 00:14:47.310
to how we as Americans
define who we are and really

00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:50.500
take into account the different
layers that each of us has.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:53.580
And all of those things, how am
I living my intersectionality,

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:56.580
well, I'm living it by doing it.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:14:58.050
If any of you follow
me on Twitter,

00:14:58.050 --> 00:15:00.630
I'm very vocal about
issues of diversity,

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:03.720
particularly in the industry
that I work in, which is media.

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:07.480
But I also created
content around this issue.

00:15:07.480 --> 00:15:11.250
And whether it's media
representation or inequality,

00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:12.930
that's my contribution to it.

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:15.626
But it comes from a place of
real experience and personal

00:15:15.626 --> 00:15:16.500
and lived experience.

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:18.627
So I hope that
answered your question.

00:15:18.627 --> 00:15:19.460
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Yeah.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:20.440
It's Your story.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:21.380
You tell it how you
want to tell it.

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:21.900
TANZINA VEGA: And I could go on.

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:23.608
MYOSHA MCAFEE: All
right, EJ, [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:23.608 --> 00:15:26.300
us a personal look [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:29.960
EJ JOHNSON: Yeah, well, I will
say that my personal experience

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:32.160
is just a lot of ups and downs.

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:37.350
A lot of almost
contradictions really.

00:15:37.350 --> 00:15:40.720
I am a black male.

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:44.310
I'm part of the LGBTQ
community as well.

00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:49.860
But also I had to learn about--

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:53.240
my struggles were different
from a lot of other people's

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:55.740
growing up, like not only do I
have to deal with black male,

00:15:55.740 --> 00:15:58.830
but now, oh, my god, I'm gay.

00:15:58.830 --> 00:15:59.820
What do I do?

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:06.330
So at the same time, I came
from a privileged family.

00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:10.740
So I didn't necessarily have
to deal with the race card

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:12.125
the first thing on the table.

00:16:12.125 --> 00:16:14.250
But you know, it's something
that my parents always

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:16.458
taught me, like this is what
our people went through.

00:16:16.458 --> 00:16:18.450
This is what you
may face one day.

00:16:18.450 --> 00:16:21.060
And eventually I had
to see that for myself.

00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:23.760
And then growing up
and then finding out,

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:28.110
holy crap, I'm different
again, here I am being gay

00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:29.370
and gender fluid.

00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:30.750
So now what do I do?

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:32.640
So that was a whole
other experience for me.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:35.730
And just because someone
might look at me,

00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:38.160
and just, oh, well,
look at this queen go.

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:40.791
You have it all, or you're
wearing fancy clothes

00:16:40.791 --> 00:16:41.790
and doing this and that.

00:16:41.790 --> 00:16:44.247
But I have my own struggles.

00:16:44.247 --> 00:16:46.080
And I think that that's
what the great thing

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:48.210
about this
intersectionality thing is

00:16:48.210 --> 00:16:54.390
is just that we are all part of
so many different communities,

00:16:54.390 --> 00:16:58.800
and they come together in
ways that might be daunting

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:02.520
and but at the same
time are also beautiful.

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:06.630
But I think that the thing is
it's so hard to not put people

00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:09.690
in boxes and just look at
one struggle or one thing

00:17:09.690 --> 00:17:11.068
that somebody else is doing.

00:17:11.068 --> 00:17:12.359
You have to look at everything.

00:17:12.359 --> 00:17:15.270
And a lot of the times that
person has to tell you,

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:18.415
and you have to just
really listen to them

00:17:18.415 --> 00:17:20.790
and listen to their stories
and listen to their struggles

00:17:20.790 --> 00:17:23.130
to understand what's going
on in their mind, what's

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:24.480
going on in their life.

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:27.459
And that's really where
I think that we're

00:17:27.459 --> 00:17:29.250
getting rid of that
kind of discrimination.

00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:31.420
We're really listening
to and looking

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:35.980
at all the different sections
that that person is in.

00:17:35.980 --> 00:17:39.280
And for me personally,
it was just

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:40.600
a lot of ups and downs for me.

00:17:40.600 --> 00:17:45.070
I thought, OK, I'm not really
dealing with this race thing,

00:17:45.070 --> 00:17:47.620
but now people are staring
because of the way I dress.

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:48.880
People are staring
because I'm holding hands

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:49.810
with some other boy.

00:17:49.810 --> 00:17:52.480
People are making comments
or snickering to me

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:54.190
and talking to me
on social media.

00:17:54.190 --> 00:17:57.850
And there's just
so much pressure.

00:17:57.850 --> 00:18:00.520
And especially after I
had a public coming out,

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:03.460
which most people don't
have to deal with.

00:18:03.460 --> 00:18:05.770
That's really when you
know the red flags raised

00:18:05.770 --> 00:18:08.929
for me, that I have to be here.

00:18:08.929 --> 00:18:10.970
I have to stand my ground,
because not everyone's

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:12.220
going to have my back.

00:18:12.220 --> 00:18:15.520
And I tried not to read a lot
of the things that people wrote

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:18.130
about me or said,
but at the same time,

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:19.679
it cannot be ignored.

00:18:19.679 --> 00:18:21.720
And of course, it stemmed
from a lot of ignorance

00:18:21.720 --> 00:18:22.870
and a lot of hate.

00:18:22.870 --> 00:18:27.370
But I just had to stay
true to who I was.

00:18:27.370 --> 00:18:28.630
I wasn't changing.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:32.842
And I'm never going to not be
me just because some sad woman

00:18:32.842 --> 00:18:33.550
in her basement--

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:34.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:36.430
--wants to come for me.

00:18:36.430 --> 00:18:43.600
But the point is it
was a lot to deal

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:46.420
with at the time, because I
was still relatively young.

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:49.780
And at the same time, I
just had to understand

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:53.660
where that type of
ignorance was coming from.

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:56.590
And that for the time being,
it's not going to change.

00:18:56.590 --> 00:18:58.180
That people can be
nice to your face

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:01.000
and people can give you hugs
and be like oh yes, yes, yes.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:02.800
But you don't really
know what they're

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.049
going home and saying about
you or what they're doing.

00:19:05.049 --> 00:19:08.320
And you have to really
do that extra work

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:11.320
to make sure that those people
know that they can't break you

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:14.800
down, and also, too, you bring
all your communities together

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:18.310
and uplift that type of
hatred, because that's

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:20.560
where we're kind of
moving but we need

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:22.090
to keep that momentum going.

00:19:22.090 --> 00:19:23.710
Because it's going
to be extremely

00:19:23.710 --> 00:19:25.667
important for the future.

00:19:25.667 --> 00:19:26.890
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Thank you.

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:29.730
So now I want to go back to
the organizing of the Women's

00:19:29.730 --> 00:19:30.230
March.

00:19:30.230 --> 00:19:32.890
And you were like at the
end there was some glory,

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:34.920
but on the way there
were some challenges.

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:36.670
LINDA SARSOUR: There's
not a lot of glory.

00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:38.045
MYOSHA MCAFEE: I
think when we're

00:19:38.045 --> 00:19:40.750
trying to figure out how
do we design solutions

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:43.030
or how do I as an
individual, I as a team,

00:19:43.030 --> 00:19:45.662
begin to actually apply
intersectional frameworks.

00:19:45.662 --> 00:19:47.620
And one thing that I
think is a common practice

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:50.124
that we grapple with here is
as soon as we start centering

00:19:50.124 --> 00:19:51.790
marginalized communities,
whether that's

00:19:51.790 --> 00:19:54.840
black folks or queer
folks or poor folks,

00:19:54.840 --> 00:19:56.950
people of the more privileged
class start looking

00:19:56.950 --> 00:19:59.530
for the side of their identity
that has disadvantage,

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:00.572
and like what about this?

00:20:00.572 --> 00:20:01.905
Why can't this be at the center?

00:20:01.905 --> 00:20:03.006
So I'll give one example.

00:20:03.006 --> 00:20:04.130
We want to talk about race.

00:20:04.130 --> 00:20:06.090
There are people like
let's talk about gender.

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:08.530
And it's a constant like,
let's make this a single issue.

00:20:08.530 --> 00:20:10.580
Let's put them in
competition with each other.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:12.440
And so I'm curious
about what it'd

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:14.805
mean to have a march that
started out with white women

00:20:14.805 --> 00:20:15.670
as organizers.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:17.080
I know there was an incredible
amount of conversation

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:18.790
about where the women of
color, were women of color

00:20:18.790 --> 00:20:20.123
even going to attend this event.

00:20:20.123 --> 00:20:22.930
But once you guys all
decided to come on board,

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:24.130
what was the conversation?

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:25.510
Like how did the
agenda have to shift,

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:27.220
how did certain
practices have to shift,

00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:28.450
what did white
women in particular,

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:30.525
what new role did they have
to take on, what new frame

00:20:30.525 --> 00:20:33.130
works did they have to walk in,
and then women of color, what

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:35.960
was their difference that
they had to engage with?

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:38.210
LINDA SARSOUR: So when the
Women's March on Washington

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:40.668
was originally announced, it
was the Million Women's March.

00:20:40.668 --> 00:20:43.450
And we were like,
educational moment.

00:20:43.450 --> 00:20:45.280
There was already a
Million Women's March.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:47.140
And I will say this in
just a little credit

00:20:47.140 --> 00:20:50.710
to those particular white
women is that they really

00:20:50.710 --> 00:20:52.674
didn't know, they had no idea.

00:20:52.674 --> 00:20:55.090
So they changed the name, and
we went to the Women's March

00:20:55.090 --> 00:20:56.464
on Washington,
with the blessings

00:20:56.464 --> 00:20:58.919
of Bernice King, who's Dr.
Martin Luther King's daughter.

00:20:58.919 --> 00:21:01.210
There was always conversations
that were happening even

00:21:01.210 --> 00:21:03.130
when we took on that name.

00:21:03.130 --> 00:21:05.380
And the skepticism that was
coming from women of color

00:21:05.380 --> 00:21:07.540
was welcomed, because we were
the skeptical women of color,

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:09.430
too, that ended up
being part of the March.

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:14.440
But I will say this, we were
not about to allow white women

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:18.580
to have a national march
where they were going

00:21:18.580 --> 00:21:22.289
to set the agenda for women
nationally and not have women

00:21:22.289 --> 00:21:23.830
of color as part of
the conversation,

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:25.663
like we were just not
going let that happen.

00:21:25.663 --> 00:21:28.180
So we took one for the team.

00:21:28.180 --> 00:21:31.330
And what happened during
the organizing of the March

00:21:31.330 --> 00:21:32.620
was that--

00:21:32.620 --> 00:21:34.630
so I remember a "New
York Times" reporter

00:21:34.630 --> 00:21:37.300
who wrote a story about
this where she was basically

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.180
trolling the Women's March
on Washington Facebook page.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:42.977
And she saw a lot of
divisive, tense conversations

00:21:42.977 --> 00:21:45.310
that were happening about why
we were talking about race

00:21:45.310 --> 00:21:48.010
and why we were kind of
pushing this conversation.

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:50.800
And she asked this
question, and she said,

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:52.750
do you think this is
going to hurt the March?

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:54.583
Who is doing your social
media and whatever?

00:21:54.583 --> 00:21:55.750
And I was like, hold up.

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:58.300
This is not an accident.

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:00.760
These conversations that
we're creating about race

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:01.660
are by design.

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:03.820
Like we were pushing those
conversations forward,

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:05.470
the way our social
media was talking

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:07.780
about the issues in an
intersectional manner

00:22:07.780 --> 00:22:09.550
was designed that way.

00:22:09.550 --> 00:22:13.090
And was it because we wanted
to create divisiveness?

00:22:13.090 --> 00:22:15.220
That divisiveness had
nothing to do with us.

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:17.140
It had to do with the
people who were feeling

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:19.024
like there were some sort of--

00:22:19.024 --> 00:22:21.190
they were offended by
something that they themselves

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:24.290
hadn't grappled with
as mostly white women.

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:26.137
So if I'm talking
to you about, you

00:22:26.137 --> 00:22:27.720
want to talk about
pay equity, but you

00:22:27.720 --> 00:22:30.320
don't want me to say you
may be a white woman not

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:32.030
getting the same pay as a man.

00:22:32.030 --> 00:22:34.190
But black and Latino
and other women of color

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:36.080
are not getting paid
the same amount as you,

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:37.700
and you don't want me
to talk about that,

00:22:37.700 --> 00:22:39.200
then you ain't
really in this forum.

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:41.564
And if you are offended
enough that you

00:22:41.564 --> 00:22:42.980
don't want to come
to the March, I

00:22:42.980 --> 00:22:45.590
think that March is going
to be just fine without you.

00:22:45.590 --> 00:22:47.090
And then the other
conversation that

00:22:47.090 --> 00:22:49.006
came up that was really
interesting in the way

00:22:49.006 --> 00:22:50.880
that we think about
are we in this together

00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:53.540
was a lot of controversy
around this idea why we didn't

00:22:53.540 --> 00:22:55.400
like highlight Hillary Clinton.

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:57.740
Like why wasn't Hillary
Clinton like our poster

00:22:57.740 --> 00:22:59.540
child for the Women's
March on Washington?

00:22:59.540 --> 00:23:01.954
Clearly, I got 20
reasons why personally,

00:23:01.954 --> 00:23:03.620
why she wasn't my
poster child, but I'll

00:23:03.620 --> 00:23:04.940
leave that to the side.

00:23:04.940 --> 00:23:06.710
But this idea that
people actually

00:23:06.710 --> 00:23:10.580
thought that we would take a
privileged, multimillionaire

00:23:10.580 --> 00:23:13.429
rich white lady that
has a dynasty to be

00:23:13.429 --> 00:23:14.720
the face of the Women's March--

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:19.100
are you out of your mind is
my personal response to that.

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:23.330
But it was really a
lot of opportunities

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:26.304
to have what Carmen Perez
calls courageous conversations.

00:23:26.304 --> 00:23:28.220
This is the reason why
we preach to the choir,

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:30.220
because we only want to
talk to people that only

00:23:30.220 --> 00:23:31.577
agree with what we have to say.

00:23:31.577 --> 00:23:33.410
And I say to women of
color and many of them

00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:35.840
are people that I only mostly
organize with women of color

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:36.980
is that I get it.

00:23:36.980 --> 00:23:39.010
I'm with you,
pain, trauma, we're

00:23:39.010 --> 00:23:40.760
tired of having to
explain to white people

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:43.250
why they got to be in
the way that we want to,

00:23:43.250 --> 00:23:45.440
but we are at a moment
right now in this country,

00:23:45.440 --> 00:23:46.790
we're all in this together.

00:23:46.790 --> 00:23:48.590
We're living under
fascism right now.

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:50.870
And in order for us to
defeat fascism or at least

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:53.460
survive under fascism, we've
got to be in this together.

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:58.520
So being able to take a little
extra time to be like, oh, OK.

00:23:58.520 --> 00:23:59.264
What about this?

00:23:59.264 --> 00:23:59.930
What about this?

00:23:59.930 --> 00:24:00.467
Read this.

00:24:00.467 --> 00:24:03.050
Did you ever read this Book did
you read Dr. Kimberley's book?

00:24:03.050 --> 00:24:03.800
Did you read that?

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:06.870
And for people to
actually say I will.

00:24:06.870 --> 00:24:08.870
And that's the people
that we were working with.

00:24:08.870 --> 00:24:11.453
People who genuinely just never
organize a day in their lives.

00:24:11.453 --> 00:24:15.050
Like for example, Bob Bland, one
of the four national co-chairs

00:24:15.050 --> 00:24:16.220
is a fashion entrepreneur.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:17.320
That's what she
does for a living.

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:19.790
She don't really need to be an
activist, although I realize

00:24:19.790 --> 00:24:21.330
that she was in her own way.

00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:22.970
She does ethical manufacturing.

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:27.064
So her job is she incubates
fashion lines ethically

00:24:27.064 --> 00:24:28.730
and within the United
States of America.

00:24:28.730 --> 00:24:31.190
So I was like do you know that
that's a form of activism?

00:24:31.190 --> 00:24:33.620
So in fact, there are women
who had different things

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:35.930
that they cared about that
they were able to bring.

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:39.620
One of them is a woman by
the name of Brianne Butler.

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:41.120
Brianne Butler was a baker.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:42.470
She bakes cakes for a living.

00:24:42.470 --> 00:24:44.576
Like the Women's March
was also an opportunity

00:24:44.576 --> 00:24:45.950
to bring ordinary
people that are

00:24:45.950 --> 00:24:48.350
not activists and in organizing
spaces and bringing them

00:24:48.350 --> 00:24:50.150
to the table and saying
what talents do you have?

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:51.260
What do you care about?

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:54.230
How can we use you
to put this forth?

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:55.850
But at the end of
the day, what we

00:24:55.850 --> 00:24:58.058
were able to do with the
Women's March on Washington,

00:24:58.058 --> 00:25:01.160
inspired by longtime work
by people like Dr. Kimberly

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:04.730
is that it was an intersectional
march that was led by women.

00:25:04.730 --> 00:25:05.840
It wasn't a women's march.

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:07.250
Because there were
men that were there,

00:25:07.250 --> 00:25:09.666
and it was also an opportunity
for us to center to climate

00:25:09.666 --> 00:25:11.630
justice, racial justice,
there were plenty

00:25:11.630 --> 00:25:12.530
of black women on the stage.

00:25:12.530 --> 00:25:14.090
And I didn't say this
earlier about myself.

00:25:14.090 --> 00:25:15.710
So I'm a Palestinian
Muslim American.

00:25:15.710 --> 00:25:16.584
I'm an Arab-American.

00:25:16.584 --> 00:25:20.210
I'm white if you want to
be technical, according

00:25:20.210 --> 00:25:21.735
to the US Census Bureau, right?

00:25:21.735 --> 00:25:22.610
So I have light skin.

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:23.660
If I took this hijab off.

00:25:23.660 --> 00:25:25.576
I'd be like any other
white lady in this room.

00:25:25.576 --> 00:25:27.710
Darker hair, but I am white.

00:25:27.710 --> 00:25:30.290
I mean, race wise.

00:25:30.290 --> 00:25:33.560
So I chose as one of
the co-chairs to center

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:35.300
black Muslim woman in the March.

00:25:35.300 --> 00:25:37.460
So for example, you
saw Alia Sharif,

00:25:37.460 --> 00:25:40.070
she's a hip hop
artist from Oakland.

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:42.080
We had Muhammad Ali's daughter.

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:44.300
We had Sister Iesha
Prime from Baltimore.

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:47.120
Like I chose to use
my own privilege

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:49.790
as a light-skinned Muslim,
who may not have privilege

00:25:49.790 --> 00:25:53.467
in the outside general society,
but within my own community,

00:25:53.467 --> 00:25:54.050
let's be real.

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:56.060
I do get more platforms
than black Muslim women

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:56.851
do in my community.

00:25:56.851 --> 00:25:59.310
So I chose at that moment
to be able to say, OK,

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:01.100
who am I centering
for my community here?

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:03.650
I'm going to center black
Muslim women voices.

00:26:03.650 --> 00:26:07.070
And at the Women's March being
able to center trans voices

00:26:07.070 --> 00:26:10.850
and center women of color
who are actually doing work

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:13.852
that is not necessarily
connected to being per se

00:26:13.852 --> 00:26:14.560
a woman of color.

00:26:14.560 --> 00:26:18.380
So for example, the
president of NRDC,

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:20.450
which is the National
Resource Defense Council,

00:26:20.450 --> 00:26:21.380
is a black woman.

00:26:21.380 --> 00:26:23.690
And she has dedicated her
life to climate justice,

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:24.270
for example.

00:26:24.270 --> 00:26:26.360
Being able to also
take people and show

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:28.610
people that I don't have
to be a Muslim woman that

00:26:28.610 --> 00:26:30.290
works on Muslim
issues, I could be

00:26:30.290 --> 00:26:32.180
a Muslim woman running
a reproductive rights

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:32.730
organization.

00:26:32.730 --> 00:26:34.610
I could be a Muslim woman
running a climate justice

00:26:34.610 --> 00:26:35.200
organization.

00:26:35.200 --> 00:26:36.570
So we did that.

00:26:36.570 --> 00:26:38.510
And we were able to
center those voices,

00:26:38.510 --> 00:26:41.090
and we were also
able to show people--

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:43.322
for example, like we
had no shame saying

00:26:43.322 --> 00:26:44.780
to someone like
Scarlett Johansson,

00:26:44.780 --> 00:26:47.155
you went over your time, and
you're getting your mic cut.

00:26:47.155 --> 00:26:52.270
Like you don't get more time
than the undocumented Pakistani

00:26:52.270 --> 00:26:53.270
girl from Staten Island.

00:26:53.270 --> 00:26:57.870
The idea that we were able
to say, yes, and by the way,

00:26:57.870 --> 00:26:59.330
FYI, you probably
don't know this.

00:26:59.330 --> 00:27:01.580
We didn't invite those
celebrities just so you know.

00:27:01.580 --> 00:27:03.170
Those were people
that came to us

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:05.260
and wanted to get down
with what we were doing.

00:27:05.260 --> 00:27:07.010
So we didn't have to
go out and reach out.

00:27:07.010 --> 00:27:10.034
The people we recruited were the
actual activists, organizers,

00:27:10.034 --> 00:27:12.200
and directly impacted people
that were at the March.

00:27:12.200 --> 00:27:14.930
So my point is that the
Women's March on Washington

00:27:14.930 --> 00:27:16.130
wasn't all glory.

00:27:16.130 --> 00:27:17.270
There was tense moments.

00:27:17.270 --> 00:27:19.520
There were moments
where, believe it or not,

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:22.160
we were in intense conversations
where I remember clearly

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:26.690
where one woman said, a white
woman said, I'm feeling,

00:27:26.690 --> 00:27:27.500
quote--

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:29.090
get ready for this one--

00:27:29.090 --> 00:27:30.950
"I'm feeling like a
second class citizen."

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:37.280
Excuse me, do you
even understand

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:40.850
for you to be able to
say what it means to be--

00:27:40.850 --> 00:27:43.430
I'm being marginalized
in this space.

00:27:43.430 --> 00:27:44.919
Excuse me.

00:27:44.919 --> 00:27:47.210
So being able to also allow
people to think and reflect

00:27:47.210 --> 00:27:48.585
on the type of
language that they

00:27:48.585 --> 00:27:50.600
use with people that
actually do fundamentally

00:27:50.600 --> 00:27:52.160
understand marginalization.

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:54.234
People who
fundamentally understand

00:27:54.234 --> 00:27:56.150
what it means to be a
second class citizen not

00:27:56.150 --> 00:27:59.060
to say that women historically
haven't, white women included,

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:01.520
haven't felt like in certain
spaces as second class

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:03.980
citizens, but to be in a
space with women of color who

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:05.510
have had loved ones--

00:28:05.510 --> 00:28:10.690
in our group-- loved ones die to
gun violence, police violence,

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:12.320
Carmen Perez's
sister, like people

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:14.690
who have been around gang
activity that has directly

00:28:14.690 --> 00:28:16.065
impacted their
family, people who

00:28:16.065 --> 00:28:18.260
understand state violence,
like in a very deep way,

00:28:18.260 --> 00:28:22.070
have not gotten jobs because
of their race or other reasons,

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:24.360
for them to hear that,
it was triggering.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:25.410
People were triggered.

00:28:25.410 --> 00:28:28.020
And so there was a
lot of hard moments.

00:28:28.020 --> 00:28:30.502
But what we ended up
manifesting at the Women's

00:28:30.502 --> 00:28:32.960
March on Washington, and this
wasn't successful everywhere.

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:35.990
There were some states where
some of the people of color

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:38.210
were like, nah.

00:28:38.210 --> 00:28:39.200
We ain't.

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.760
And we weren't
responsible for that,

00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:43.425
because it was a decentralized
method of organizing, where

00:28:43.425 --> 00:28:45.050
there were people
who individually took

00:28:45.050 --> 00:28:46.550
the branding of the
Women's March on Washington

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:47.480
and made it their own.

00:28:47.480 --> 00:28:48.646
We saw that as a first step.

00:28:48.646 --> 00:28:51.740
But we did this in an
intersectional way.

00:28:51.740 --> 00:28:55.631
We made sure that the agenda not
only gave women of color seats

00:28:55.631 --> 00:28:58.130
at the table, but that the women
of color were on the table.

00:28:58.130 --> 00:28:59.970
Like if you weren't
talking about us,

00:28:59.970 --> 00:29:01.970
and we weren't at the
center of the conversation

00:29:01.970 --> 00:29:04.794
as the most directly impacted
in this current environment,

00:29:04.794 --> 00:29:06.460
we didn't want anything
to do with that.

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:10.700
But also being able to
see the power of centering

00:29:10.700 --> 00:29:13.410
women of color, not just their
issues, but them as leaders.

00:29:13.410 --> 00:29:16.220
So we came to the Women's March
on Washington, I was like look.

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:18.370
You ain't putting my cute
face as a token Muslim,

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:20.390
like that's just not happening.

00:29:20.390 --> 00:29:21.770
I want to be a boss here.

00:29:21.770 --> 00:29:23.450
And I want to have
a leadership role.

00:29:23.450 --> 00:29:24.140
What do you want to do?

00:29:24.140 --> 00:29:26.265
I want to fundraise, I
think that I'm good at that.

00:29:26.265 --> 00:29:28.070
They were like, you
want to fundraise?

00:29:28.070 --> 00:29:29.150
Yes, I want to fundraise.

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:31.670
And the reason why I
wanted to fundraise also

00:29:31.670 --> 00:29:33.620
is because I wanted
to teach people

00:29:33.620 --> 00:29:36.920
about being able to organize
a movement that is powered

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:39.397
by the people, which is
not a concept people often

00:29:39.397 --> 00:29:39.980
to understand.

00:29:39.980 --> 00:29:42.860
They always think we need to
have Wal-Mart in the back,

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:45.830
or even, to be honest,
even Google, right?

00:29:45.830 --> 00:29:47.629
Even if you're a
corp like Patagonia,

00:29:47.629 --> 00:29:49.670
there are some companies
that you may see and say

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:51.530
they're corporate responsible.

00:29:51.530 --> 00:29:54.682
They're whatever, you
know what I'm saying.

00:29:54.682 --> 00:29:55.640
And I said, guess what?

00:29:55.640 --> 00:29:57.090
We could do this
without corporations.

00:29:57.090 --> 00:29:59.510
I will not stand on a stage
that has Coca-Cola, or Pepsi

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:01.760
or any corporation behind me.

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:03.981
And white folks in
particular were really

00:30:03.981 --> 00:30:06.230
like I don't think you're
going to be able to do that.

00:30:06.230 --> 00:30:07.340
And we did it.

00:30:07.340 --> 00:30:09.860
The March on Washington
was funded by the people--

00:30:09.860 --> 00:30:12.980
by the $27, the $50,
the $20, the $10.

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:16.760
And it was also by the partners,
Planned Parenthood, MoveOn.org,

00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:19.021
ACLU, and those type of folks
that came in and gave us

00:30:19.021 --> 00:30:19.520
that money.

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:22.784
So being able to have
these hard conversations,

00:30:22.784 --> 00:30:24.950
being able to be women of
color and say we will only

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:27.251
work under these
circumstances and being heard,

00:30:27.251 --> 00:30:29.750
and that's why I want to give
the white women that we worked

00:30:29.750 --> 00:30:32.930
with credit, because they
could have been like nah,

00:30:32.930 --> 00:30:35.240
this is our, we
started this, that's

00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:36.680
not how we envisioned it.

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:37.850
So you all need to step out.

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:41.120
We'll go find some other women
of color who aren't going to be

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:43.160
like y'all, and make us
do whatever we wanted.

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:44.300
And they were like no.

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:45.650
Maybe we're going to
learn something from you,

00:30:45.650 --> 00:30:47.630
and maybe we are going
to do intersexual

00:30:47.630 --> 00:30:49.546
and that's what happened
at the Women's March.

00:30:49.546 --> 00:30:51.470
So I want all that to
say that I give credit

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:53.210
to those white
women who listened.

00:30:53.210 --> 00:30:54.770
We actually said this to them.

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:56.840
Can you just listen
for a second?

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:59.590
So Tamika Mallory, who many
of you may know, is quite,

00:30:59.590 --> 00:31:01.875
she got a little spice
in her, you know?

00:31:01.875 --> 00:31:02.750
She's from the Bronx.

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:05.631
Like she's no joke, like
she puts it out there,

00:31:05.631 --> 00:31:06.630
you take it or leave it.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:09.300
And one day, she said,
do you know my story?

00:31:09.300 --> 00:31:11.180
And when she shares that
her son's father was

00:31:11.180 --> 00:31:14.270
shot and killed when her
son was only two years old,

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:17.120
found in a ditch two
weeks after he was dead,

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:18.470
and she had to witness that.

00:31:18.470 --> 00:31:20.303
And her son's growing
up without his father,

00:31:20.303 --> 00:31:22.870
living in a poor
community in the Bronx

00:31:22.870 --> 00:31:25.730
and growing up in a civil
rights community and family

00:31:25.730 --> 00:31:27.590
and has seen people
in her family arrested

00:31:27.590 --> 00:31:30.260
and incarcerated, told
these very personal stories

00:31:30.260 --> 00:31:31.160
about her family.

00:31:31.160 --> 00:31:33.290
Then the women were like--
because you will never

00:31:33.290 --> 00:31:34.410
experience what
Tamika Mallory has.

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:36.350
So don't ask her why
she's angry all the time.

00:31:36.350 --> 00:31:37.490
She got reason to be angry.

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:39.800
And when Carmen tells
you that her sister was

00:31:39.800 --> 00:31:41.667
buried on her 17th birthday.

00:31:41.667 --> 00:31:43.250
So when it was
Carmen's 17th birthday,

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:45.140
her sister, who was
only two years older

00:31:45.140 --> 00:31:47.330
was buried on her birthday
in Oxnard, California.

00:31:47.330 --> 00:31:51.110
She grew up in a community
that was [INAUDIBLE] with gang

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:52.832
violence and poverty.

00:31:52.832 --> 00:31:54.290
And when you hear
their stories, it

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.345
makes you sit back
and say whoa ho.

00:31:56.345 --> 00:31:59.270
I'm never going to experience
what these ladies saw.

00:31:59.270 --> 00:31:59.900
You know what?

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:01.070
I've got something
to learn from them.

00:32:01.070 --> 00:32:03.111
So all that it required
was for women to sit back

00:32:03.111 --> 00:32:05.060
not be defensive and
learn and listen,

00:32:05.060 --> 00:32:08.840
and that's how we got to January
21st, which was up until today,

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:10.730
and I hope folks want
to do bigger than that,

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:12.600
it is the largest
protest in US history.

00:32:12.600 --> 00:32:16.157
And it happened this year in
your generation on our watch

00:32:16.157 --> 00:32:17.990
and I hope that we
continue to do that work.

00:32:17.990 --> 00:32:19.031
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Thank you.

00:32:19.031 --> 00:32:25.800
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:25.800 --> 00:32:28.699
So I'm going to go
to Dr. Kim next,

00:32:28.699 --> 00:32:30.240
asking the question
of her, how do we

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.240
be intentional about
being intersectional?

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:36.090
And I want to build on
what Linda just laid out.

00:32:36.090 --> 00:32:37.740
And if you missed
it, I just want

00:32:37.740 --> 00:32:39.156
to hit you with
the bullet points,

00:32:39.156 --> 00:32:41.820
you know, at Google, we like the
hit me with the bullet point.

00:32:41.820 --> 00:32:43.590
Women of color, I
think what she laid out

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:45.709
is being willing to ask
tough questions to people

00:32:45.709 --> 00:32:48.000
in the dominant group, being
willing to educate but not

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:49.230
like necessarily yourself.

00:32:49.230 --> 00:32:51.220
Here are some books if
you want to read it.

00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:55.240
So you don't sit yourself in
this racial battle fatigue.

00:32:55.240 --> 00:32:57.522
You are assertive at
the negotiation table.

00:32:57.522 --> 00:32:58.230
She's very clear.

00:32:58.230 --> 00:33:00.900
Look, you're not going
to use me as a token.

00:33:00.900 --> 00:33:02.700
You're not going to
put my face up there.

00:33:02.700 --> 00:33:04.200
We're not going to have
Coca-Cola in the background,

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:06.930
like very assertive in setting
parameters and boundaries

00:33:06.930 --> 00:33:08.550
around how are we
going to do this,

00:33:08.550 --> 00:33:11.820
rather than being at the
effect of the experience there.

00:33:11.820 --> 00:33:13.500
Using the privilege
she does have--

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:14.860
and I think that's really
important to acknowledge

00:33:14.860 --> 00:33:15.660
when you're a person of color.

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:17.790
Like we're all walking
around with these identities

00:33:17.790 --> 00:33:19.248
of both privilege
and disadvantage.

00:33:19.248 --> 00:33:22.530
So she's naming, as a
lighter-skinned Muslim woman,

00:33:22.530 --> 00:33:25.500
like what privilege do I
have here that I can center

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:27.060
somebody else's experience?

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:28.920
So thinking about
that as a black woman,

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:30.210
are there people
amongst that community

00:33:30.210 --> 00:33:30.920
that I need to be centering?

00:33:30.920 --> 00:33:32.586
Because I'm privileged
in a certain way.

00:33:32.586 --> 00:33:35.850
I am highly educated at an
elite Ivy League university.

00:33:35.850 --> 00:33:38.550
There's definitely room for me
to make space for other women,

00:33:38.550 --> 00:33:41.630
other lived experiences,
other frameworks.

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:43.670
And then equalizing,
despite status.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:48.821
What was the famous
person, I forgot her name.

00:33:48.821 --> 00:33:49.570
Was it something--

00:33:49.570 --> 00:33:50.070
KIM CRENSHAW:
Scarlett Johansson.

00:33:50.070 --> 00:33:51.120
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Yes,
Scarlett Johansson.

00:33:51.120 --> 00:33:52.710
It's like you don't
get more talk time

00:33:52.710 --> 00:33:54.870
than an undocumented immigrant.

00:33:54.870 --> 00:33:57.370
So I mean even thinking about
equalizing on that level.

00:33:57.370 --> 00:33:59.940
And I think for white women in
particular, humility, I think,

00:33:59.940 --> 00:34:02.430
came up a lot, a
willingness to learn came up

00:34:02.430 --> 00:34:06.270
and a willingness to follow,
like regardless of your title,

00:34:06.270 --> 00:34:07.950
your position, you fall back.

00:34:07.950 --> 00:34:09.659
Somebody else in a
marginalized community

00:34:09.659 --> 00:34:11.162
has certain
experiences, which does

00:34:11.162 --> 00:34:12.870
create a certain amount
of knowledge that

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:14.699
informs what we should do next.

00:34:14.699 --> 00:34:16.739
That's the high
level bullet point.

00:34:16.739 --> 00:34:19.679
Dr. Kim we're going to
add to that list of how

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:21.305
do we be intentional.

00:34:21.305 --> 00:34:23.429
Add to the list-- how to
be intentional about being

00:34:23.429 --> 00:34:23.930
intersectional?

00:34:23.930 --> 00:34:25.930
Because there are a lot
of people who are trying

00:34:25.930 --> 00:34:27.530
to figure out what to do next.

00:34:27.530 --> 00:34:29.100
KIM CRENSHAW: Yeah.

00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:31.650
Those are all, I
think, absolutely

00:34:31.650 --> 00:34:34.050
essential steps to take.

00:34:34.050 --> 00:34:38.760
I think what I would add
to it is an understanding

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:43.350
that the challenge is
to multiple communities,

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:45.489
not just to white women.

00:34:45.489 --> 00:34:48.060
So the March was a context
in which the conversation

00:34:48.060 --> 00:34:51.750
was about deprivileging
and shifting

00:34:51.750 --> 00:34:53.904
the frame to broaden it.

00:34:53.904 --> 00:34:55.320
But it's also the
case that that's

00:34:55.320 --> 00:35:00.294
a conversation that needs to
be had within institutions.

00:35:00.294 --> 00:35:01.710
It's a conversation
that has to be

00:35:01.710 --> 00:35:04.740
had within racial
justice struggles.

00:35:04.740 --> 00:35:08.040
It's a conversation that has to
be had within LGBTQ struggles.

00:35:08.040 --> 00:35:11.460
So in each of these spaces,
the same kind of moves

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:14.790
often have to be made
in order to make sure

00:35:14.790 --> 00:35:17.010
that the intersectional
ways that certain kinds

00:35:17.010 --> 00:35:21.450
of experiences play
out are actually

00:35:21.450 --> 00:35:23.280
at the center of the movement.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:28.350
This conversation
started with a video clip

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:31.860
from our organization on a
campaign called Say Her Name.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:35.610
And Say Her Name actually
came out of a march.

00:35:35.610 --> 00:35:39.360
We were in a march
in New York City

00:35:39.360 --> 00:35:43.380
around the non-indictment of the
officer responsible for killing

00:35:43.380 --> 00:35:45.300
Eric Gardner.

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:48.240
There were thousands and
thousands of people there

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:51.570
who had been drawn
because of that injustice.

00:35:51.570 --> 00:35:54.270
And in the process
of marching, we

00:35:54.270 --> 00:35:57.190
were calling out men who had
been killed by the police.

00:35:57.190 --> 00:35:59.790
And there was a whole spate
of them as many of you

00:35:59.790 --> 00:36:04.950
know, Michael Brown,
Tamir Rice, Freddie Gray.

00:36:04.950 --> 00:36:07.070
We started naming
some of the women who

00:36:07.070 --> 00:36:10.170
had been killed
at the same time,

00:36:10.170 --> 00:36:15.990
Michelle Cusseaux was killed
within two weeks of Mike Brown,

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:17.730
and no one knew her name.

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:21.000
Ara Russer, Tunisia
Anderson was killed a week

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.790
before Tamir Rice, by the
same police department.

00:36:23.790 --> 00:36:26.340
No one knew knew her name.

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:31.380
So some part of Say Her Name
is to build on the frame that

00:36:31.380 --> 00:36:32.165
already exists.

00:36:32.165 --> 00:36:35.220
So we know that
state-sanctioned violence

00:36:35.220 --> 00:36:38.580
has been racialized throughout
the history of this country.

00:36:38.580 --> 00:36:39.610
We have images.

00:36:39.610 --> 00:36:40.290
We have frames.

00:36:40.290 --> 00:36:41.956
We have quick ways
of thinking about it.

00:36:41.956 --> 00:36:45.120
A lot of people think
in terms of lynching.

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:48.180
They think in terms of
the ways that police

00:36:48.180 --> 00:36:49.500
have contributed to that.

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:52.950
But they think of that in
a gender exclusive way.

00:36:52.950 --> 00:36:56.250
So our challenge was to take
that frame and broaden it.

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:58.710
To say, everything
you think you know

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:02.040
about state-sanctioned
violence, yes, that's true.

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:04.230
And also this.

00:37:04.230 --> 00:37:05.910
And also this.

00:37:05.910 --> 00:37:09.270
So in the same ways
that police have often

00:37:09.270 --> 00:37:13.720
said that Mike Brown
was like a monster.

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:17.490
He was framed as someone who
had to be put down with a gun

00:37:17.490 --> 00:37:19.230
because he couldn't be stopped.

00:37:19.230 --> 00:37:21.690
Actually, police say the
same thing about black women

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:23.166
who are killed.

00:37:23.166 --> 00:37:24.540
And when it's said
about a woman,

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:27.690
it's clear that it's a racial
thing that's happening.

00:37:27.690 --> 00:37:34.410
There's no way that a woman
could be overtaken and tasered

00:37:34.410 --> 00:37:41.580
to death by seven different men
as happened in one of the cases

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:43.320
that we highlight,
tasered to death,

00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:47.520
because they said she posed
a risk to their lives.

00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:49.800
This is something that's real.

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:52.140
It's something that happened.

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:54.960
It is a real risk
that black women face.

00:37:54.960 --> 00:37:57.630
So we try to build
intersectional awareness

00:37:57.630 --> 00:38:00.820
based on the single issue
ideas that people have.

00:38:00.820 --> 00:38:03.900
If you think this is what
state-sanctioned violence looks

00:38:03.900 --> 00:38:06.600
like from a racial
justice point of view,

00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:09.390
this is what happens when
you add gender to it.

00:38:09.390 --> 00:38:12.240
And it's the same
on the other side.

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:16.720
There is a significant movement
around gender-based violence.

00:38:16.720 --> 00:38:18.630
Rape and sexual
abuse is something

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:24.210
that women have organized
around for at least 50 years.

00:38:24.210 --> 00:38:27.000
You don't get
women's organizations

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.940
organizing around
rape and sexual abuse

00:38:29.940 --> 00:38:32.520
by police officers.

00:38:32.520 --> 00:38:36.750
But just last year a
police officer in Oklahoma

00:38:36.750 --> 00:38:41.460
was convicted for raping and
abusing eight black women.

00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:45.630
What made it possible for
him to rape and abuse eight

00:38:45.630 --> 00:38:46.920
black women?

00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:49.560
It's intersectional
vulnerability.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:51.690
They're black women,
historically black women

00:38:51.690 --> 00:38:53.400
have not been believed.

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:55.020
They were poor women.

00:38:55.020 --> 00:38:57.990
Many of them were
system-involved women,

00:38:57.990 --> 00:38:59.970
meaning they had
a criminal record.

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:02.820
These were all things that
made this officer believe

00:39:02.820 --> 00:39:05.640
that he could do what he
could do with impunity

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:07.450
and nothing was going to happen.

00:39:07.450 --> 00:39:10.800
So that's the intersectional
vulnerability.

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:15.870
The problem is neither the
gender-based violence movement,

00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:19.080
nor quite honestly, the
anti-racist movement

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:22.470
against police violence
took that case up.

00:39:22.470 --> 00:39:23.730
Why is that?

00:39:23.730 --> 00:39:25.410
It fell between the cracks.

00:39:25.410 --> 00:39:28.410
It fell between, the
way that you think

00:39:28.410 --> 00:39:30.170
about race-based violence.

00:39:30.170 --> 00:39:32.760
It's shooting, it's
beating, it's not raping.

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:34.980
And it fell between
the way people think

00:39:34.980 --> 00:39:37.210
about violence against women.

00:39:37.210 --> 00:39:40.080
That's usually seen as
private, not as something

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:42.760
that the state is
responsible for.

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:45.570
So the basic message
is if we want

00:39:45.570 --> 00:39:48.790
to think how to
deepen our practice,

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:51.180
we have to ask
concrete questions.

00:39:51.180 --> 00:39:53.730
This is the way
gender is imagined

00:39:53.730 --> 00:39:59.250
to be a factor in a workplace.

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:00.510
Is it the only way?

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:02.880
Are there other ways that
we can think about it?

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:07.110
Or to flip the script, ,
yes, I'm subject to gender.

00:40:07.110 --> 00:40:09.780
But what advantages
do I have that I'm

00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:12.600
allowed to use in
order to navigate

00:40:12.600 --> 00:40:16.680
this space that another
woman who is not white has?

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:18.270
I'd like to sometimes
think about it

00:40:18.270 --> 00:40:22.260
as the difference
between can the boss

00:40:22.260 --> 00:40:26.100
imagine you in his
living room or can he

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:28.120
imagine you in the locker room?

00:40:28.120 --> 00:40:31.440
So if you're a man
of color, you do

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:33.180
have that racial disadvantage.

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:36.420
But you do have
shared masculinity,

00:40:36.420 --> 00:40:40.800
and sometimes you can navigate
your disadvantage with that.

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:44.580
Or if you're a white woman,
yes, gender might be a factor.

00:40:44.580 --> 00:40:47.100
But you do have
social similarity.

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:50.490
You do have a common
social cultural history

00:40:50.490 --> 00:40:52.140
that you might be able to use.

00:40:52.140 --> 00:40:55.500
But that woman of color has
neither of those things.

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:58.470
And if you really want
to have some proof of it,

00:40:58.470 --> 00:41:01.050
look at some of the
studies on mentoring.

00:41:01.050 --> 00:41:03.280
Mentorship, everyone
knows, is one

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:05.550
of the most significant
things that you can have

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:07.890
to help you navigate upward.

00:41:07.890 --> 00:41:11.880
Mentors are most likely to share
some kind of social identity

00:41:11.880 --> 00:41:13.350
with their mentees.

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:16.840
So if you can share being a
man or share being a woman,

00:41:16.840 --> 00:41:18.390
you're more likely
to be mentored

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:21.280
than if you can't share
either one of those things.

00:41:21.280 --> 00:41:24.480
So a practice that says, look,
we know mentorship is good.

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:26.940
But we know it also
doesn't equally

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:30.000
extend across our
entire workforce, that's

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.430
a moment for intersectional
intervention.

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:35.280
Those are the kinds of moments
that you can make a difference

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:38.460
by being aware of the
different situation of some

00:41:38.460 --> 00:41:39.439
of your workforce.

00:41:39.439 --> 00:41:40.480
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Thank you.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:42.855
So now we're going to make a
hard left just a little bit.

00:41:42.855 --> 00:41:46.080
And because we're in Texas, and
there were some policy changes

00:41:46.080 --> 00:41:48.120
that took place,
was it yesterday,

00:41:48.120 --> 00:41:50.250
around the transgender
bathroom policy,

00:41:50.250 --> 00:41:51.889
I wanted us to gently
talk about that.

00:41:51.889 --> 00:41:54.180
And EJ, I'll start with you,
but anybody else who wants

00:41:54.180 --> 00:41:55.860
to hop in on it.

00:41:55.860 --> 00:41:58.320
So last May the Department
of Education and Justice

00:41:58.320 --> 00:42:00.180
issued joint guidance
directing schools

00:42:00.180 --> 00:42:03.150
to let transgender students
use facilities that correspond

00:42:03.150 --> 00:42:06.900
with their gender identity based
on the Obama administration's

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:09.540
interpretation of Title
IX, the federal law that

00:42:09.540 --> 00:42:12.240
prohibits sex
discrimination in schools

00:42:12.240 --> 00:42:13.710
to include gender identity.

00:42:13.710 --> 00:42:17.040
Trump's administration rescinded
this guidance yesterday

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:19.170
without offering a replacement.

00:42:19.170 --> 00:42:23.160
Supporters of this say that
it's not anti-LGBTQ sentiment,

00:42:23.160 --> 00:42:25.357
but federal overreach
into state matters,

00:42:25.357 --> 00:42:27.190
and that schools should
be able to determine

00:42:27.190 --> 00:42:29.290
this policy at the local level.

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:31.690
I'm curious about what would
be your recommendations, not

00:42:31.690 --> 00:42:33.730
just to schools, but
any organization.

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:35.500
Because I think including
our organization

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:37.585
is grappling with
this type of policy.

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:43.120
EJ JOHNSON: Well,
I actually was just

00:42:43.120 --> 00:42:46.420
reminded of a story when
I was in high school.

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:52.990
And I remember that we
had our LGBT club fought

00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:57.940
for having more gender
neutral bathrooms in school.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:00.164
And I even remember
talking to my friends

00:43:00.164 --> 00:43:01.580
and we were like,
well, who cares?

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:03.850
I mean, like you have your
mens, you have your womens,

00:43:03.850 --> 00:43:06.080
and you go to the bathroom.

00:43:06.080 --> 00:43:11.440
And now here I am,
being me and doing me,

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:19.030
and realize, OK, like so today
if my outfit requires a skirt,

00:43:19.030 --> 00:43:20.740
where do I go?

00:43:20.740 --> 00:43:22.185
You know, where
am I comfortable?

00:43:22.185 --> 00:43:24.310
I don't have a problem
peeing in the men's bathroom

00:43:24.310 --> 00:43:29.590
in whatever outfit I'm in, but
some people do, a lot of people

00:43:29.590 --> 00:43:30.430
do.

00:43:30.430 --> 00:43:36.460
So I just don't
understand why we wouldn't

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:39.040
have more of those
bathrooms where people

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:41.130
can be comfortable
or at least have

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:42.880
those conversations
or an open environment

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:45.190
where we can at
least talk about it.

00:43:45.190 --> 00:43:48.920
And I think that whether
in schools or in offices,

00:43:48.920 --> 00:43:50.620
I mean, those are
the types of places

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:53.590
that we need to be having these
conversations about what's

00:43:53.590 --> 00:43:56.300
making our community
comfortable,

