00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:07.240
But I do think it's a question
of curiosity and openness

00:55:07.240 --> 00:55:09.686
to hearing and being
uncomfortable and asking

00:55:09.686 --> 00:55:10.810
the uncomfortable question.

00:55:10.810 --> 00:55:13.230
I'm surprised that there's
only one question in the room.

00:55:13.230 --> 00:55:15.730
I know there's probably a lot
of questions in people's minds

00:55:15.730 --> 00:55:18.490
right now, right, thinking
should I, shouldn't I?

00:55:18.490 --> 00:55:19.639
It's OK to ask it.

00:55:19.639 --> 00:55:22.180
Like I have these conversations
in the newsroom all the time.

00:55:22.180 --> 00:55:24.721
And I'd say I'd rather us have
the uncomfortable conversation

00:55:24.721 --> 00:55:28.390
now, behind the scenes, when
we're just trying to figure out

00:55:28.390 --> 00:55:31.540
this story or this video, than
broadcast something that's

00:55:31.540 --> 00:55:32.590
inaccurate.

00:55:35.560 --> 00:55:41.050
KIM CRENSHAW: I want to embrace
the idea of discomfort that

00:55:41.050 --> 00:55:45.700
has been put on the
table and normalize

00:55:45.700 --> 00:55:50.440
discomfort and denormalize
comfort with injustice.

00:55:50.440 --> 00:55:54.340
That's the real shift right now.

00:55:54.340 --> 00:55:58.990
I mean we could just take
an example of whatever space

00:55:58.990 --> 00:55:59.680
we're in.

00:55:59.680 --> 00:56:01.450
I teach at two law schools.

00:56:01.450 --> 00:56:05.830
Many times I am the only person
that looks like me in the room

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:07.570
that I'm in.

00:56:07.570 --> 00:56:10.870
Never am I in a
room where there's

00:56:10.870 --> 00:56:14.920
anywhere close to parity
between people who look like me

00:56:14.920 --> 00:56:17.200
and the rest of the population.

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:20.140
I think we're also sitting in
a room where if we were honest,

00:56:20.140 --> 00:56:22.150
we would look around
and say there's

00:56:22.150 --> 00:56:26.650
a certain lack of parity
between the way this space is

00:56:26.650 --> 00:56:28.780
constituted and
the world outside.

00:56:28.780 --> 00:56:30.760
It's not unique to Google.

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:32.770
It's everywhere.

00:56:32.770 --> 00:56:35.140
And it's on every part of it.

00:56:35.140 --> 00:56:42.670
If you go to a family court, or
if you go to a benefit shelter,

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:45.940
that place doesn't look
like the rest of America.

00:56:45.940 --> 00:56:50.860
So when we live in a society
when it's still predictable,

00:56:50.860 --> 00:56:53.290
by just looking at
someone, whether they're

00:56:53.290 --> 00:56:57.040
likely to be the CEO or
the person who cleans,

00:56:57.040 --> 00:57:01.390
we still have a hierarchy
that's racially coded.

00:57:01.390 --> 00:57:03.190
This is called
decoding race, right?

00:57:03.190 --> 00:57:06.490
You're not going to be able
to decode it if you don't know

00:57:06.490 --> 00:57:08.620
something needs to be decoded.

00:57:08.620 --> 00:57:10.930
It's not something out there.

00:57:10.930 --> 00:57:14.200
It's something everywhere
we happen to be.

00:57:14.200 --> 00:57:17.200
So the question is,
what kind of orientation

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:22.000
do we want to have as we
began the process of decoding?

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:24.040
Why do we want to decode?

00:57:24.040 --> 00:57:26.560
What are the questions
that we want to ask?

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:29.320
I would say that some questions
that we might want to ask

00:57:29.320 --> 00:57:33.580
are, what are the societal
processes, the dynamics that

00:57:33.580 --> 00:57:35.500
create the space that we're in?

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:37.180
How did it happen?

00:57:37.180 --> 00:57:40.110
And what story are
we telling ourselves

00:57:40.110 --> 00:57:41.750
if we're not asking
that question?

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:43.840
Because you've got to
have a story about why

00:57:43.840 --> 00:57:45.400
your space looks the way it is.

00:57:45.400 --> 00:57:47.800
You've got to have a story
about why your neighborhood is

00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:49.120
made up the way it is.

00:57:49.120 --> 00:57:52.060
You've got to have a story about
why your church looks the way--

00:57:52.060 --> 00:57:53.200
you've got to have a story.

00:57:53.200 --> 00:57:55.750
You might not be telling
yourself what it is.

00:57:55.750 --> 00:57:57.610
But you have a story.

00:57:57.610 --> 00:58:01.390
And many times that story
is deeply problematic.

00:58:01.390 --> 00:58:03.490
It's often a story about
well, people are just

00:58:03.490 --> 00:58:05.380
choosing different things.

00:58:05.380 --> 00:58:08.170
Or people just have
different talents,

00:58:08.170 --> 00:58:11.140
or they have different
cultural habits.

00:58:11.140 --> 00:58:14.960
They have the ability to
withstand instant gratification

00:58:14.960 --> 00:58:15.759
is a story.

00:58:15.759 --> 00:58:17.300
I mean there are
all sorts of stories

00:58:17.300 --> 00:58:20.090
that we tell ourselves about
how our institutions look

00:58:20.090 --> 00:58:21.170
the way they do.

00:58:21.170 --> 00:58:23.510
And when we don't
challenge those stories,

00:58:23.510 --> 00:58:25.970
we reproduce those systems.

00:58:25.970 --> 00:58:29.780
Because we tend to reproduce the
same thing that got us there.

00:58:29.780 --> 00:58:35.270
When you're asking what
should the next CEO look like,

00:58:35.270 --> 00:58:38.720
or what should be a
qualification for doing x job,

00:58:38.720 --> 00:58:43.700
you're likely to base the answer
on what the system has already

00:58:43.700 --> 00:58:45.020
produced.

00:58:45.020 --> 00:58:46.700
But what that
system has produced

00:58:46.700 --> 00:58:48.990
didn't come out of nowhere.

00:58:48.990 --> 00:58:50.510
It wasn't something
that just got

00:58:50.510 --> 00:58:54.800
constituted without race and
without gender playing a role.

00:58:54.800 --> 00:59:00.440
So by saying discomfort, I mean
being uncomfortable not asking

00:59:00.440 --> 00:59:03.560
those questions-- being
uncomfortable just going along

00:59:03.560 --> 00:59:09.170
like it's all OK, being brave
enough to say it's up to us

00:59:09.170 --> 00:59:12.740
to decide how much of this
we can produce differently.

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:18.110
How we can be creative about
how we conceptualize what

00:59:18.110 --> 00:59:21.470
a good candidate is,
to be creative enough

00:59:21.470 --> 00:59:24.380
to think about how this job
could be done differently,

00:59:24.380 --> 00:59:27.650
to be bold enough to
say we're not satisfied

00:59:27.650 --> 00:59:30.350
with our society
looking the way it does,

00:59:30.350 --> 00:59:32.930
or this institution
looking the way it does.

00:59:32.930 --> 00:59:34.820
It's those kind of
discomforts that I

00:59:34.820 --> 00:59:36.870
think we should want to create.

00:59:36.870 --> 00:59:40.040
And we should want to be
uncomfortable with not

00:59:40.040 --> 00:59:41.840
doing that.

00:59:41.840 --> 00:59:45.860
MYOSHA MCAFEE: Deep
inquiry and reflection.

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:49.250
Other questions?

00:59:49.250 --> 00:59:51.686
AUDIENCE: So if I think about
what the many policies that

00:59:51.686 --> 00:59:53.310
bother me about the
new administration,

00:59:53.310 --> 00:59:55.731
it's the education,
school choice,

00:59:55.731 --> 00:59:58.230
and how that's going to impact
women of color in particular.

00:59:58.230 --> 01:00:00.780
So I just want to hear your
thoughts on what we can do,

01:00:00.780 --> 01:00:01.950
what you think that
impact could be,

01:00:01.950 --> 01:00:03.908
and how we can change
that trajectory possibly.

01:00:08.709 --> 01:00:10.750
KIM CRENSHAW: Well, I'll
start with just a couple

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:12.180
of observations
I'm sure everyone

01:00:12.180 --> 01:00:14.610
has some thoughts about this.

01:00:14.610 --> 01:00:18.210
So I'm going to say a word
that gets talked about a lot,

01:00:18.210 --> 01:00:21.060
but isn't often defined.

01:00:21.060 --> 01:00:23.500
We're in a neoliberal moment.

01:00:23.500 --> 01:00:29.340
By that I'm trying to capture
the idea that everything

01:00:29.340 --> 01:00:31.830
is being reduced to markets.

01:00:31.830 --> 01:00:35.340
And in that, most things
are being privatized, which

01:00:35.340 --> 01:00:37.650
includes public education.

01:00:37.650 --> 01:00:41.700
So the moves that we're going
to be seeing in public education

01:00:41.700 --> 01:00:46.710
and in health and in
pretty much everything else

01:00:46.710 --> 01:00:49.950
are moves to greater and
greater privatization.

01:00:49.950 --> 01:00:52.590
With greater
privatization, typically

01:00:52.590 --> 01:00:56.100
has become greater
levels of inequality,

01:00:56.100 --> 01:00:59.370
greater levels of
hierarchy, greater levels

01:00:59.370 --> 01:01:01.470
of people of color
particularly not being

01:01:01.470 --> 01:01:03.480
able to make it to the top.

01:01:03.480 --> 01:01:07.860
So I think that we can more
or less predict the areas that

01:01:07.860 --> 01:01:12.720
will be more likely impactful
on communities of color

01:01:12.720 --> 01:01:14.400
are those areas
where people of color

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:17.970
actually had a greater role
in the public production

01:01:17.970 --> 01:01:19.500
of the good.

01:01:19.500 --> 01:01:21.570
Education is one of them.

01:01:21.570 --> 01:01:23.700
Government in general
is another one.

01:01:23.700 --> 01:01:26.940
Why is it that people of color
actually are more in government

01:01:26.940 --> 01:01:28.080
than other places?

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:31.170
Well, let's start
asking those questions.

01:01:31.170 --> 01:01:33.450
I think there are
clear answers to that,

01:01:33.450 --> 01:01:36.480
and consequently there are
clear answers to the outcome.

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:38.880
I'll say this as
just a last point.

01:01:38.880 --> 01:01:40.650
Because I think
the tendency when

01:01:40.650 --> 01:01:44.130
people hear why are certain
institutions looking

01:01:44.130 --> 01:01:46.530
the way they do, including
the government, which

01:01:46.530 --> 01:01:49.690
is far more integrated
than private space,

01:01:49.690 --> 01:01:53.580
there is a sense that that's
the product of discrimination

01:01:53.580 --> 01:01:55.810
that happened a long time ago.

01:01:55.810 --> 01:01:58.500
I don't think there is a sense
that there are things happening

01:01:58.500 --> 01:02:00.090
right here and right now.

01:02:00.090 --> 01:02:02.160
They might not look
like the kind of things

01:02:02.160 --> 01:02:04.020
that we are used to before.

01:02:04.020 --> 01:02:05.391
There aren't white only signs.

01:02:05.391 --> 01:02:06.390
People aren't picketing.

01:02:06.390 --> 01:02:09.490
They're not throwing bricks
at Martin Luther King.

01:02:09.490 --> 01:02:13.290
But there are other ways in
which pipelines are racially

01:02:13.290 --> 01:02:17.550
constructed, so that, yes, more
people are in public education

01:02:17.550 --> 01:02:18.180
than private.

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:21.540
Yes, more people are in
certain jobs than others.

01:02:21.540 --> 01:02:24.390
And then here's the last
thing, yes, more people

01:02:24.390 --> 01:02:26.970
have wealth than others.

01:02:26.970 --> 01:02:29.400
So Tanzina was talking
about the wealth gap.

01:02:29.400 --> 01:02:31.860
Let me add this last piece.

01:02:31.860 --> 01:02:36.270
Women of color have a median net
worth, Latinas and black women,

01:02:36.270 --> 01:02:38.730
of $0.

01:02:38.730 --> 01:02:42.840
I just want you to think
about what that means.

01:02:42.840 --> 01:02:45.450
Close to a majority
of women of color

01:02:45.450 --> 01:02:49.200
don't have the amount of wealth
that it takes to buy a Big Mac.

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:53.610
I mean wealth is what you have
after all of your deficits,

01:02:53.610 --> 01:02:57.360
all your debts are
subtracted from your assets.

01:02:57.360 --> 01:03:00.420
Wealth is what allows you to
provide for your children.

01:03:00.420 --> 01:03:03.240
Wealth is what allows you to
take care of a sick parent

01:03:03.240 --> 01:03:05.130
and also send your
kid to summer camp.

01:03:05.130 --> 01:03:07.560
Wealth is what allows
you to move to a place

01:03:07.560 --> 01:03:09.510
where you can have
access to healthy food

01:03:09.510 --> 01:03:11.750
or you can have
access to recreation.

01:03:11.750 --> 01:03:15.900
Wealth is the thing that
allows you to actually sustain

01:03:15.900 --> 01:03:17.910
yourself during
the kind of crises

01:03:17.910 --> 01:03:21.900
that will always be happening
in an economy like ours.

01:03:21.900 --> 01:03:25.020
When we can say that one
part of our population

01:03:25.020 --> 01:03:27.210
has a median net
wealth of zero it's

01:03:27.210 --> 01:03:30.960
telling you that the pipelines
that their children will be in

01:03:30.960 --> 01:03:33.840
are not going to lead
to places like this.

01:03:33.840 --> 01:03:37.290
So it's going all the way
back to the baselines,

01:03:37.290 --> 01:03:42.210
who has what in this society,
and that's not natural.

01:03:42.210 --> 01:03:44.796
So maybe you know,
maybe you don't--

01:03:44.796 --> 01:03:47.730
at a time when the
government played the biggest

01:03:47.730 --> 01:03:49.740
role in creating
the neighborhoods

01:03:49.740 --> 01:03:54.000
we have was in the federal
housing, the creation

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:55.590
of federal housing.

01:03:55.590 --> 01:04:01.620
They spent $120 billion,
these are in 1940s dollars,

01:04:01.620 --> 01:04:03.510
to create suburbs.

01:04:03.510 --> 01:04:06.540
These suburbs were created
as all white enclaves

01:04:06.540 --> 01:04:08.410
by the government.

01:04:08.410 --> 01:04:11.130
So what does it mean to have
bought a house in the suburbs

01:04:11.130 --> 01:04:18.000
in 1940, for let's say,
$25,000 versus being forced

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:22.410
to live in a ghetto for about
the same amount in terms

01:04:22.410 --> 01:04:24.200
of your monthly housing costs?

01:04:24.200 --> 01:04:26.830
That gave you a difference
between having a house back

01:04:26.830 --> 01:04:28.240
then and an apartment.

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:30.210
But now, three
generations later,

01:04:30.210 --> 01:04:32.260
the one who bought the house?

01:04:32.260 --> 01:04:34.650
What are they able to
do with that equity?

01:04:34.650 --> 01:04:36.550
They can send kids to college.

01:04:36.550 --> 01:04:38.970
They can send kids
to graduate school.

01:04:38.970 --> 01:04:41.880
You can go around the
world if you want to.

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:45.360
The family that had to
settle for the apartment

01:04:45.360 --> 01:04:47.520
in the ghetto, probably
still is living

01:04:47.520 --> 01:04:49.616
in an apartment in a ghetto.

01:04:49.616 --> 01:04:51.240
We'll look at that
and say, well, those

01:04:51.240 --> 01:04:54.660
are just natural realities.

01:04:54.660 --> 01:04:57.240
They are the product
of public policy,

01:04:57.240 --> 01:04:59.340
so the point is,
if public policy

01:04:59.340 --> 01:05:04.530
can create racialized class,
then it can uncreate it.

01:05:04.530 --> 01:05:06.870
We just have to be willing
to see that these are

01:05:06.870 --> 01:05:08.660
the products of public policy.

01:05:08.660 --> 01:05:10.160
That's the challenge
that I'm trying

01:05:10.160 --> 01:05:12.449
to encourage everybody to do.

01:05:12.449 --> 01:05:14.990
TANZINA VEGA: And I want you to
think on an individual level,

01:05:14.990 --> 01:05:15.160
too.

01:05:15.160 --> 01:05:15.868
Yeah, please.

01:05:15.868 --> 01:05:22.570
[APPLAUSE]

01:05:22.570 --> 01:05:24.730
I mentioned before I grew
up in public housing.

01:05:24.730 --> 01:05:26.720
I also went to public school.

01:05:26.720 --> 01:05:27.820
I have a master's degree.

01:05:27.820 --> 01:05:30.030
I have an undergraduate degree.

01:05:30.030 --> 01:05:31.840
And those are all
from public school.

01:05:31.840 --> 01:05:33.980
And why is that the case?

01:05:33.980 --> 01:05:36.520
Because it was a
financial decision.

01:05:36.520 --> 01:05:38.740
You wouldn't think that
because of where I work

01:05:38.740 --> 01:05:40.930
and like I said,
the big fancy job.

01:05:40.930 --> 01:05:45.190
And I hope you like my
outfit, things like that.

01:05:45.190 --> 01:05:48.550
But the fact of the matter is
growing up in that environment,

01:05:48.550 --> 01:05:51.462
without having that
equity to pass on,

01:05:51.462 --> 01:05:53.420
it doesn't only afford
you those opportunities,

01:05:53.420 --> 01:05:54.870
it means I can't take a break.

01:05:54.870 --> 01:05:57.590
It's very hard to take a break.

01:05:57.590 --> 01:06:00.370
I want you guys to understand
when you're looking at resumes,

01:06:00.370 --> 01:06:02.070
because this comes up a lot,
especially when you're thinking

01:06:02.070 --> 01:06:03.760
we've got to hire brown people.

01:06:03.760 --> 01:06:04.269
Right?

01:06:04.269 --> 01:06:05.810
We've got to hire
these brown people.

01:06:05.810 --> 01:06:06.940
So you're looking at
all the brown people

01:06:06.940 --> 01:06:08.148
that work in your department.

01:06:08.148 --> 01:06:10.510
And you're like, they've
got to know somebody, right?

01:06:10.510 --> 01:06:13.051
And then you get all the resumes
in, and then the first thing

01:06:13.051 --> 01:06:15.760
you do, and I know you all
do this is look for what?

01:06:18.510 --> 01:06:22.282
Harvard, Stanford,
yada, yada, we're

01:06:22.282 --> 01:06:23.490
going to go on and on, right?

01:06:23.490 --> 01:06:25.170
But do you look at
state university?

01:06:25.170 --> 01:06:25.720
Uh uh.

01:06:25.720 --> 01:06:26.220
That's out.

01:06:26.220 --> 01:06:28.680
That's in the circular
file immediately, right?

01:06:28.680 --> 01:06:32.730
Right there you're
eliminating a talent pool

01:06:32.730 --> 01:06:34.830
that you haven't
even considered.

01:06:34.830 --> 01:06:36.540
And there's nothing
wrong with Harvard

01:06:36.540 --> 01:06:39.450
and Stanford and Columbia and
all these wonderful places.

01:06:39.450 --> 01:06:41.370
I'll be potentially
teaching at some

01:06:41.370 --> 01:06:42.780
of those places in my future.

01:06:42.780 --> 01:06:46.050
So the fact of the matter is
these are amazing institutions,

01:06:46.050 --> 01:06:48.455
but we cannot
continue to assume,

01:06:48.455 --> 01:06:50.580
especially when you're
looking for talent of color,

01:06:50.580 --> 01:06:53.490
you're only looking
for the unicorn.

01:06:53.490 --> 01:06:55.560
The unicorns are
amazing but unicorns

01:06:55.560 --> 01:06:58.230
live in many different
parts of this population.

01:06:58.230 --> 01:07:00.960
I guarantee you that
you get somebody who's

01:07:00.960 --> 01:07:03.210
worked so hard to get there.

01:07:03.210 --> 01:07:07.200
And to them getting a job at
Google or at "The New York

01:07:07.200 --> 01:07:09.690
Times" or one of these
places, it's like--

01:07:09.690 --> 01:07:12.060
I mean it's unthinkable.

01:07:12.060 --> 01:07:15.030
You're creating a
pathway to prosperity.

01:07:15.030 --> 01:07:18.480
You're creating a change
in someone's class level

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:19.262
potentially.

01:07:19.262 --> 01:07:21.720
And that's not to say that it's
magic, and all of a sudden.

01:07:21.720 --> 01:07:24.390
Because I have that
fancy job, and I'm not,

01:07:24.390 --> 01:07:26.670
my net worth isn't like--

01:07:26.670 --> 01:07:28.710
believe me I'm still
shopping discount.

01:07:28.710 --> 01:07:30.365
But the point is
that that matters.

01:07:30.365 --> 01:07:32.490
And you all, again, bringing
it back to yourselves,

01:07:32.490 --> 01:07:35.090
really take a look at when
you're examining people.

01:07:35.090 --> 01:07:36.870
Because that's a big
part of, I think,

01:07:36.870 --> 01:07:40.270
where we tend to block a
black person or Latino person,

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:43.620
but only if they went to
da, da, da, da, da place.

01:07:43.620 --> 01:07:45.010
It eliminates too many people.

01:07:47.680 --> 01:07:50.130
AUDIENCE: It seems like the
media is attending to whatever

01:07:50.130 --> 01:07:52.450
is the most important to
the most people at that

01:07:52.450 --> 01:07:56.770
time, which leads to a very
reactionary type of response

01:07:56.770 --> 01:07:58.700
from everyone.

01:07:58.700 --> 01:07:59.630
How do we avoid that?

01:07:59.630 --> 01:08:02.770
How do we be more proactive and
avoid this sort of firefighting

01:08:02.770 --> 01:08:04.990
mentality where we're
only attacking the issues

01:08:04.990 --> 01:08:06.250
that Twitter cares about?

01:08:06.250 --> 01:08:08.045
TANZINA VEGA: Thank
you for that question.

01:08:08.045 --> 01:08:09.670
I'm assuming you
wanted me to answer it

01:08:09.670 --> 01:08:13.972
as a member of the media,
the mainstream media.

01:08:13.972 --> 01:08:15.820
Woo!

01:08:15.820 --> 01:08:21.055
All right, I tell people I
was just on a panel a week ago

01:08:21.055 --> 01:08:23.050
for this talk on
race and policing.

01:08:23.050 --> 01:08:25.479
And a similar
question was raised.

01:08:25.479 --> 01:08:27.700
And I said you, as
media consumers,

01:08:27.700 --> 01:08:31.990
have a tremendous
amount of power.

01:08:31.990 --> 01:08:33.160
I'll give you the example.

01:08:33.160 --> 01:08:38.590
At "The New York Times," I
created the race beat in 2013.

01:08:38.590 --> 01:08:41.571
I said, went to the then
executive editor Jill Abramson,

01:08:41.571 --> 01:08:43.029
and said, look,
I've got this idea.

01:08:43.029 --> 01:08:44.570
I think these stories
are doing well.

01:08:44.570 --> 01:08:47.380
This is pre-Ferguson, just
so we have a timeline.

01:08:47.380 --> 01:08:49.100
So, oh, yeah, this
is a great idea.

01:08:49.100 --> 01:08:49.600
Let's do it.

01:08:49.600 --> 01:08:50.330
I said great.

01:08:50.330 --> 01:08:53.679
I went from doing what I
was doing on the media desk

01:08:53.679 --> 01:08:54.934
to covering this beat.

01:08:54.934 --> 01:08:56.350
And I think I was
the first Latina

01:08:56.350 --> 01:08:59.170
to found a beat like
that at "The Times."

01:08:59.170 --> 01:09:01.810
Not to say "The Times" hadn't
covered race in the past,

01:09:01.810 --> 01:09:02.830
it had.

01:09:02.830 --> 01:09:07.220
But it had been about 13 years
since they did it systemically.

01:09:07.220 --> 01:09:09.760
And so I was suggesting that
we sit down and have me do it

01:09:09.760 --> 01:09:13.310
and kick it off, and that
I think went very well.

01:09:13.310 --> 01:09:15.240
We had a lot of great stories.

01:09:15.240 --> 01:09:16.870
You can look them
up yourselves look

01:09:16.870 --> 01:09:20.290
I've covered everything from
black women and discipline

01:09:20.290 --> 01:09:24.100
in schools to Asian-American
elder care issues to how

01:09:24.100 --> 01:09:26.470
Arab-Americans and Latino
Americans are answering

01:09:26.470 --> 01:09:29.200
the census form, like
who's white, who's not.

01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:31.640
I mean we sort of went all over.

01:09:31.640 --> 01:09:34.479
And these stories got
really good responses.

01:09:34.479 --> 01:09:37.120
After about a year,
"The Times" decided

01:09:37.120 --> 01:09:39.670
we don't need this beat,
for whatever reason,

01:09:39.670 --> 01:09:41.050
and we're killing it.

01:09:41.050 --> 01:09:45.040
What they didn't realize,
and what I told them was,

01:09:45.040 --> 01:09:47.582
this isn't going to sit
well with our audience.

01:09:47.582 --> 01:09:48.290
Well, guess what?

01:09:48.290 --> 01:09:49.330
It didn't.

01:09:49.330 --> 01:09:52.720
The audience took to Twitter.

01:09:52.720 --> 01:09:54.310
We had a public
editor at "The Times,"

01:09:54.310 --> 01:09:56.215
an ombudsman at "The Times."

01:09:56.215 --> 01:09:58.090
At that time, it was
Margaret Sullivan, who's

01:09:58.090 --> 01:09:59.780
now at "The Washington Post."

01:09:59.780 --> 01:10:04.210
And just email, just
people were just like done.

01:10:04.210 --> 01:10:06.670
Like they were like, what
are you talking about?

01:10:06.670 --> 01:10:10.957
And it just became this huge
issue where the public editor

01:10:10.957 --> 01:10:13.540
called and said, look, I've got
to cover this for "The Times."

01:10:13.540 --> 01:10:16.360
So that's not awkward, right,
I'm working at the company,

01:10:16.360 --> 01:10:20.862
but now I'm going to be the
subject of an internal public--

01:10:20.862 --> 01:10:22.570
not a review, but
really it's essentially

01:10:22.570 --> 01:10:24.144
an answer to our public.

01:10:24.144 --> 01:10:26.560
That's what the ombudsman is
for to say, wait, everybody's

01:10:26.560 --> 01:10:27.220
upset.

01:10:27.220 --> 01:10:32.680
Let's interview and hold this
institution's feet to the fire.

01:10:32.680 --> 01:10:36.730
At the center of that,
totally cool, not a problem.

01:10:36.730 --> 01:10:38.380
It was very difficult
to see that,

01:10:38.380 --> 01:10:41.500
but it was also really
heartening to show that wow,

01:10:41.500 --> 01:10:42.550
we get results.

01:10:42.550 --> 01:10:43.870
Your readers can get results.

01:10:43.870 --> 01:10:45.940
It was covered in
"Columbia Journalism

01:10:45.940 --> 01:10:50.961
Review," NPR, "National Review,"
I mean all these places--

01:10:50.961 --> 01:10:51.460
I'm sorry.

01:10:51.460 --> 01:10:53.210
"The New Republic,"
not "National Review."

01:10:53.210 --> 01:10:55.520
That would have been
a whole other story.

01:10:55.520 --> 01:10:58.749
So we got a lot of
coverage about this issue.

01:10:58.749 --> 01:11:00.040
And I wasn't being interviewed.

01:11:00.040 --> 01:11:02.770
It was just about
the issue at large.

01:11:02.770 --> 01:11:05.140
So long story short,
they brought it back.

01:11:05.140 --> 01:11:07.840
I left, but they
brought it back.

01:11:07.840 --> 01:11:09.880
And now they're attempting
in their own way

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:12.820
to try and cover
race in America.

01:11:12.820 --> 01:11:14.500
I wish them the best.

01:11:14.500 --> 01:11:17.140
But I look at that
as an opportunity.

01:11:17.140 --> 01:11:19.910
And it was really interesting
to see the audience say, wait

01:11:19.910 --> 01:11:20.410
a minute.

01:11:20.410 --> 01:11:21.860
This is not what we want.

01:11:21.860 --> 01:11:24.730
So you guys have a
tremendous amount of power.

01:11:24.730 --> 01:11:27.730
You also are inundated
with media left and right

01:11:27.730 --> 01:11:31.460
from every corner of
the world at this point.

01:11:31.460 --> 01:11:33.790
I'm considering taking
Twitter off my phone,

01:11:33.790 --> 01:11:35.090
because I just can't.

01:11:35.090 --> 01:11:37.759
And I have to do
this for a living.

01:11:37.759 --> 01:11:39.550
You have to pay attention
to the people who

01:11:39.550 --> 01:11:42.190
are writing the content
or shooting the content

01:11:42.190 --> 01:11:44.590
or making the content that
you want to see and support

01:11:44.590 --> 01:11:48.310
that content, whether it
means subscribing, watching,

01:11:48.310 --> 01:11:51.430
clicking, e-mailing, sending
a letter to the editor,

01:11:51.430 --> 01:11:52.540
or whatever it is.

01:11:52.540 --> 01:11:56.716
Because ultimately that's
how you change the narrative.

01:11:56.716 --> 01:11:58.090
That's the work
I'm trying to do.

01:11:58.090 --> 01:11:59.340
It was shut down at one place.

01:11:59.340 --> 01:12:00.506
I brought it someplace else.

01:12:00.506 --> 01:12:02.740
And said all right, maybe
it won't be shut down here.

01:12:02.740 --> 01:12:07.341
But I'm just one of x thousands
and thousands of voices

01:12:07.341 --> 01:12:07.840
out there.

01:12:07.840 --> 01:12:11.830
So I try to do my part
and elevate my stories

01:12:11.830 --> 01:12:14.410
and signal boost my stories
to get out there and try

01:12:14.410 --> 01:12:16.494
to tell these narratives
that aren't getting told.

01:12:16.494 --> 01:12:19.118
And there are many other people
that are trying to do the same,

01:12:19.118 --> 01:12:20.530
but they need to be supported.

01:12:23.412 --> 01:12:24.870
LINDA SARSOUR: So
I think sometimes

01:12:24.870 --> 01:12:26.280
we're asked to do either-or.

01:12:26.280 --> 01:12:28.380
I think we do kind of
still have to be prepared

01:12:28.380 --> 01:12:30.030
to do rapid response in crisis.

01:12:30.030 --> 01:12:32.190
Like people always
say to me, why

01:12:32.190 --> 01:12:34.560
are you always outraged
when black people

01:12:34.560 --> 01:12:35.846
are killed by the police?

01:12:35.846 --> 01:12:36.970
Like that's just how it is.

01:12:36.970 --> 01:12:39.240
And I say to people,
look, it is how it is.

01:12:39.240 --> 01:12:40.197
It's been how it is.

01:12:40.197 --> 01:12:41.280
But I want to be outraged.

01:12:41.280 --> 01:12:42.990
And don't take my
humanity away from me

01:12:42.990 --> 01:12:44.659
and tell me that I
shouldn't be outraged

01:12:44.659 --> 01:12:46.950
every time a black person is
killed at the hands of law

01:12:46.950 --> 01:12:48.040
enforcement.

01:12:48.040 --> 01:12:50.330
So what Twitter has
done, it has its benefits

01:12:50.330 --> 01:12:54.090
in that it allows me, sitting
in Brooklyn, New York,

01:12:54.090 --> 01:12:56.460
to figure out that there
is a young man named

01:12:56.460 --> 01:12:59.320
Mike Brown in Ferguson that just
got shot by a police officer.

01:12:59.320 --> 01:13:02.010
It allows me to be connected
to those very human stories

01:13:02.010 --> 01:13:04.485
that if we as a
society don't elevate,

01:13:04.485 --> 01:13:06.210
ain't nobody care
about Mike Brown.

01:13:06.210 --> 01:13:08.070
Nobody cares about Sandra Bland.

01:13:08.070 --> 01:13:11.070
So it really is props to the
young people who figured out

01:13:11.070 --> 01:13:14.240
to take a public platform
to basically be able to say

01:13:14.240 --> 01:13:16.020
you will not ignore our pain.

01:13:16.020 --> 01:13:18.750
You will not ignore the blood
on the streets in our community.

01:13:18.750 --> 01:13:21.360
So there is that
opportunity to just

01:13:21.360 --> 01:13:23.400
be able to say, yes,
maybe Sandra Bland

01:13:23.400 --> 01:13:25.410
was a trending hashtag.

01:13:25.410 --> 01:13:26.610
Praise the Lord that it was.

01:13:26.610 --> 01:13:28.260
Because I would have
never learned her story.

01:13:28.260 --> 01:13:30.240
I would have never been
able to say her name.

01:13:30.240 --> 01:13:33.400
But to the other parallel
that we could use,

01:13:33.400 --> 01:13:34.830
I'm always in crisis response.

01:13:34.830 --> 01:13:36.900
Like I'm always ready
to do rapid response.

01:13:36.900 --> 01:13:38.520
But I also understand
the importance

01:13:38.520 --> 01:13:41.010
of building longevity and
building sustainability

01:13:41.010 --> 01:13:42.180
in our communities.

01:13:42.180 --> 01:13:44.760
So while we're not
organizing for Sandra Bland,

01:13:44.760 --> 01:13:46.579
how are we preventing
another black woman

01:13:46.579 --> 01:13:48.120
from getting shot
by a police officer

01:13:48.120 --> 01:13:53.340
or being killed in a cell
in custody of our state,

01:13:53.340 --> 01:13:54.170
basically.

01:13:54.170 --> 01:13:56.290
And I think what we
often do is we get--

01:13:56.290 --> 01:13:58.080
and this is why I
always say to people,

01:13:58.080 --> 01:13:59.880
ain't no time for
part-time progressives,

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:01.464
ain't no time for
part-time activists.

01:14:01.464 --> 01:14:03.463
You're either coming in
here to invest your time

01:14:03.463 --> 01:14:05.010
or you get out of
our way, because I

01:14:05.010 --> 01:14:08.670
don't want to see you, right,
at that protest that one time.

01:14:08.670 --> 01:14:11.040
I'm not saying that that's
not beneficial to show up.

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:13.262
But I want to know
where you are tomorrow,

01:14:13.262 --> 01:14:14.220
and the day after that.

01:14:14.220 --> 01:14:16.230
Because when you leave
here, there's still

01:14:16.230 --> 01:14:17.630
someone else that's impacted.

01:14:17.630 --> 01:14:20.040
That person has not
come back to life.

01:14:20.040 --> 01:14:23.550
And oftentimes those very
people that we protest for still

01:14:23.550 --> 01:14:24.610
don't get justice.

01:14:24.610 --> 01:14:27.990
Everybody-- you can name any
trending hashtag in the past

01:14:27.990 --> 01:14:29.400
year and a half--

01:14:29.400 --> 01:14:31.620
not one of those
people got justice.

01:14:31.620 --> 01:14:34.590
So we didn't even win
those smaller fights.

01:14:34.590 --> 01:14:38.250
So being able to organize,
being able to give resources

01:14:38.250 --> 01:14:40.560
to the very local organizations
on the ground in places

01:14:40.560 --> 01:14:43.030
like Ferguson, being
able to say, OK,

01:14:43.030 --> 01:14:45.480
who's in Texas organizing
around Sandra Bland.

01:14:45.480 --> 01:14:47.500
What kind of resources
do those people need?

01:14:47.500 --> 01:14:49.860
How can I as a Googler
be able to provide?

01:14:49.860 --> 01:14:52.110
Maybe I can't do it in
my official capacity,

01:14:52.110 --> 01:14:53.289
but I may be an engineer.

01:14:53.289 --> 01:14:55.080
I may know how to build
a website for them.

01:14:55.080 --> 01:14:58.500
I may know how to help
them fix their algorithm so

01:14:58.500 --> 01:15:00.840
that whatever story they got
is going out even farther.

01:15:00.840 --> 01:15:02.950
We all got something to
give to the movement.

01:15:02.950 --> 01:15:05.220
So for me, it's
like yes, show up.

01:15:05.220 --> 01:15:06.210
Yes, be outraged.

01:15:06.210 --> 01:15:08.017
It's OK that there's
a trending hashtag.

01:15:08.017 --> 01:15:09.600
The question is,
what are you offering

01:15:09.600 --> 01:15:11.490
so that next time,
god forbid, there

01:15:11.490 --> 01:15:13.650
is to be something that
happens in that community,

01:15:13.650 --> 01:15:16.170
they got more resources
than they had six months ago

01:15:16.170 --> 01:15:18.690
when another person went
down in their community.

01:15:18.690 --> 01:15:22.230
So I think for me, it's like
we could stay rapid response

01:15:22.230 --> 01:15:23.100
and crisis response.

01:15:23.100 --> 01:15:24.930
And we, by the way, are going
to have to do a lot of that

01:15:24.930 --> 01:15:26.255
under this administration.

01:15:26.255 --> 01:15:28.080
Just letting y'all
know, get ready.

01:15:28.080 --> 01:15:28.890
I'm already tired.

01:15:28.890 --> 01:15:30.580
It's only been in
like five weeks.

01:15:30.580 --> 01:15:34.770
But really understanding,
like communities of color,

01:15:34.770 --> 01:15:36.651
we just are always
like, oh, man.

01:15:36.651 --> 01:15:38.150
We're just being
hit from every way,

01:15:38.150 --> 01:15:39.900
and we never just get
the time to be left.

01:15:39.900 --> 01:15:42.120
We would like to reflect
and have a retreat

01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:45.570
and figure out how to do asset
mapping and what we need.

01:15:45.570 --> 01:15:47.640
And we try that, we attempt it.

01:15:47.640 --> 01:15:49.927
The minute we leave
that retreat on Monday,

01:15:49.927 --> 01:15:51.510
someone else is shot
in our community,

01:15:51.510 --> 01:15:53.080
a family is about
to be deported,

01:15:53.080 --> 01:15:56.040
a mosque is vandalized,
this one gets--

01:15:56.040 --> 01:15:58.290
we just are always distracted.

01:15:58.290 --> 01:16:00.810
So the question for us is how
do we build sustainability,

01:16:00.810 --> 01:16:02.900
and then how do our
white allies, who

01:16:02.900 --> 01:16:06.450
aren't easily distracted
because they don't have

01:16:06.450 --> 01:16:10.800
the same priorities or they're
not as directly impacted as we

01:16:10.800 --> 01:16:13.560
are, which was why the
Women's March on Washington

01:16:13.560 --> 01:16:14.940
was as successful as it is.

01:16:14.940 --> 01:16:17.454
I'll give you an example.

01:16:17.454 --> 01:16:18.870
A lot of the people
that did the--

01:16:18.870 --> 01:16:21.203
so for example, graphic
designer was like, we coming in.

01:16:21.203 --> 01:16:23.275
We're going to do your branding.

01:16:23.275 --> 01:16:24.150
I didn't have to ask.

01:16:24.150 --> 01:16:26.710
I was like just, I would
have just slapped anything.

01:16:26.710 --> 01:16:28.230
I don't even care.

01:16:28.230 --> 01:16:30.750
The website, the
social media, people

01:16:30.750 --> 01:16:31.854
who were like, we got you.

01:16:31.854 --> 01:16:32.520
You do the work.

01:16:32.520 --> 01:16:33.810
You set the policy agenda.

01:16:33.810 --> 01:16:35.601
You do the outreach,
you call the partners,

01:16:35.601 --> 01:16:36.780
you do what you're good at.

01:16:36.780 --> 01:16:39.010
We'll do all that other
technological-- whatever.

01:16:39.010 --> 01:16:41.010
And a lot of these people
do work at tech firms.

01:16:41.010 --> 01:16:43.197
And that's why we had
such a big apparatus.

01:16:43.197 --> 01:16:45.780
And people were like, where did
they get those resources from?

01:16:45.780 --> 01:16:47.460
It cost us zero.

01:16:47.460 --> 01:16:49.410
It was people who own
tech firms and said

01:16:49.410 --> 01:16:50.250
this is what we want to do.

01:16:50.250 --> 01:16:52.041
This is what we want
to offer the movement.

01:16:52.041 --> 01:16:54.090
And by the way,
those same people

01:16:54.090 --> 01:16:56.280
didn't bounce on January 21st.

01:16:56.280 --> 01:17:00.090
Those people are still
maintaining the infrastructure,

01:17:00.090 --> 01:17:03.099
hosting our website, making sure
that our stuff is maintained,

01:17:03.099 --> 01:17:04.140
that it's still up today.

01:17:04.140 --> 01:17:07.050
So think about
being able to say,

01:17:07.050 --> 01:17:09.870
it's OK to be doing rapid
response and crisis response,

01:17:09.870 --> 01:17:12.720
but how do we think about
longevity, sustainability,

01:17:12.720 --> 01:17:15.780
and building a movement
that lives outside of us

01:17:15.780 --> 01:17:20.040
and lives beyond every
individual case of outrage

01:17:20.040 --> 01:17:22.419
that we are in
almost on a daily.

01:17:22.419 --> 01:17:23.460
MYOSHA MCAFEE: All right.

01:17:23.460 --> 01:17:25.910
So let's thank our
panelists first.

01:17:25.910 --> 01:17:34.730
[APPLAUSE]

01:17:34.730 --> 01:17:37.080
And because this
is Google, I know

01:17:37.080 --> 01:17:38.770
some takeaways I just
want to land with.

01:17:38.770 --> 01:17:41.660
I tried to summarize some of the
points that you all laid out.

01:17:41.660 --> 01:17:43.934
And I think you're
wondering what can I

01:17:43.934 --> 01:17:44.850
walk out of here with.

01:17:44.850 --> 01:17:46.230
I think the first
piece of advice

01:17:46.230 --> 01:17:48.790
is the current status quo
that we have right now,

01:17:48.790 --> 01:17:50.394
to not see it as normal.

01:17:50.394 --> 01:17:51.810
So if you are
working in staffing,

01:17:51.810 --> 01:17:53.670
if you're working in
any type of organization

01:17:53.670 --> 01:17:55.180
where you're taking
a look at diversity,

01:17:55.180 --> 01:17:56.888
if you're taking a
look at whether or not

01:17:56.888 --> 01:17:59.220
this place is inclusive,
the way things

01:17:59.220 --> 01:18:01.200
exist right now is
something that was created.

01:18:01.200 --> 01:18:03.120
And it was created by
the people in the room,

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:07.370
in the office, not some external
arm or some force outside of us

01:18:07.370 --> 01:18:08.400
that's being created.

01:18:08.400 --> 01:18:10.410
So I think Dr. Crenshaw
invited us to say,

01:18:10.410 --> 01:18:11.946
let's look at
what's here, what we

01:18:11.946 --> 01:18:13.320
see as normal, as
our day to day,

01:18:13.320 --> 01:18:15.260
and it's not something
that's normal.

01:18:15.260 --> 01:18:17.010
It's not something
that's out of my hands.

01:18:17.010 --> 01:18:18.870
And so engage in that
deep inquiry process

01:18:18.870 --> 01:18:20.460
of how is this created now.

01:18:20.460 --> 01:18:22.560
And then think about what
is my responsibility,

01:18:22.560 --> 01:18:24.399
I think was said a
few times up here.

01:18:24.399 --> 01:18:26.190
The second thing is to
develop an awareness

01:18:26.190 --> 01:18:27.606
of our own personal
power, so this

01:18:27.606 --> 01:18:29.574
sense that this is too
big for me to handle.

01:18:29.574 --> 01:18:31.740
I think we have great
examples of people who are all

01:18:31.740 --> 01:18:33.540
engaged in the work,
put their talent

01:18:33.540 --> 01:18:35.490
and their creativity
combined together

01:18:35.490 --> 01:18:36.990
to begin to disrupt things.

01:18:36.990 --> 01:18:38.850
Great examples of
that happening here.

01:18:38.850 --> 01:18:41.500
And you're human, just
as they're human, right?

01:18:41.500 --> 01:18:43.480
And what they can
do, you can do.

01:18:43.480 --> 01:18:45.480
The third thing is
actually, instead

01:18:45.480 --> 01:18:48.952
of asking the question of what
about me, when someone starts

01:18:48.952 --> 01:18:50.910
centering their experience,
to ask the question

01:18:50.910 --> 01:18:52.290
what can I offer?

01:18:52.290 --> 01:18:54.480
And really asking the
question of who around me

01:18:54.480 --> 01:18:57.360
is encountering multiple
forms of violence,

01:18:57.360 --> 01:18:59.527
multiple forms of
disadvantage, and it

01:18:59.527 --> 01:19:01.860
doesn't matter what your
identity is, but actually think

01:19:01.860 --> 01:19:02.850
about that.

01:19:02.850 --> 01:19:05.160
Particularly when we're
centering an issue that makes

01:19:05.160 --> 01:19:07.069
you personally uncomfortable.

01:19:07.069 --> 01:19:08.610
I just want to drive
that point home.

01:19:08.610 --> 01:19:10.068
If it makes you
uncomfortable, it's

01:19:10.068 --> 01:19:13.820
probably the issue we
need to be talking about.

01:19:13.820 --> 01:19:16.840
And then finally, I love this
last talk about infrastructure.

01:19:16.840 --> 01:19:18.060
So I know that people
are trying to figure out,

01:19:18.060 --> 01:19:19.620
given what their roles are,
particularly if they're

01:19:19.620 --> 01:19:22.170
technical in nature, or they
don't see the direct connection

01:19:22.170 --> 01:19:24.030
to it, really thinking about
what's my talent, what's

01:19:24.030 --> 01:19:25.170
my gift, what's my skill?

01:19:25.170 --> 01:19:28.001
And how can I lend it to
whatever the causes the issue

01:19:28.001 --> 01:19:28.500
is?

01:19:28.500 --> 01:19:30.420
And notice, she didn't
describe somebody

01:19:30.420 --> 01:19:31.740
going there and asking for it.

01:19:31.740 --> 01:19:33.614
She described
people who offered.

01:19:33.614 --> 01:19:35.280
And so really be
thinking about how do I

01:19:35.280 --> 01:19:38.410
step up in offering my talent
and gifts to this position.

01:19:38.410 --> 01:19:38.910
All right.

01:19:38.910 --> 01:19:39.810
Thank you all for your time.

01:19:39.810 --> 01:19:41.018
Thank you for your attention.

01:19:41.018 --> 01:19:44.060
